1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 d6 {Very common, but not best. White will pin the
Knight, killing Black's counterplay.} 4. Bb5 Bd7 5. Nf3 Be7 6. O-O {
White prefers simplicity.} (6. Bxc6 {leads to a long, semi-forced sequence:}
6... Bxc6 7. fxe5 dxe5 8. Nxe5 Bxe4 9. Nxf7 (9. Nxe4 Qd4 10. d3 Qxe5 11. O-O {
gives White only the slightest edge.}) 9... Bxc2 10. Nxd8 $1 Bxd1 11. Ne6 Kd7
12. Nxc7 Kxc7 13. Kxd1 $16 {and White has an extra pawn for the endgame.}) (6.
d3) 6... exf4 7. d4 g5 8. Nd5 $1 Nh6 (8... Nf6 9. Nxg5 Nxd5 10. exd5 Bxg5 11.
dxc6 bxc6 12. Bd3 $16 {Black has an extra pawn for the moment, but his pawns
are a mess and White will soon win the pawn on f4.}) 9. h4 g4 10. Bxf4 $1 gxf3
11. Bxh6 fxg2 $2 12. Rxf7 $1 (12. Rxf7 Kxf7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 (13... Ke6 14. Qf5#)
14. Nf6+ $1 {Clearing the d5 square.} (14. Bc4 {also works.}) 14... Bxf6 15.
Qd5+ Be6 16. Qxe6#) 1-0

