1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 {This move is the first key move in the Vienna Game. White
makes it hard for Black to play ...d5 -- hard for him to make a perfect center.
} 2... Nc6 {Black does the same thing to White, copying his moves.} 3. f4 {
White offers a pawn sacrifice to pull the e-pawn away from e5. If Black takes
the pawn, White can play Nf3 and then d4, making a perfect center after all.}
3... d6 {Black defends the pawn on e5 rather than taking White's gambit.} 4.
Nf3 {White plays a good developing move that puts pressure on e5. Right now
White cannot win a pawn there, but this move keeps Black under pressure.} 4...
a6 {Black is afraid of a pin and plays this move to stop it. But the move is
not really very good -- it does not bring a piece out, so White gets ahead in
the race to bring out his pieces.} 5. Bc4 {This is an excellent square for the
Bishop, aiming at the weak spot on f7. That square is defended only by Black's
King. Watch how White takes advantage of this in the next few moves!} 5... Bg4
{Black pins White's Knight to the Queen. In the opening of a chess game, pins
against the Queen are tricky. Sometimes the Knight cannot move, but sometimes
it can!} 6. fxe5 {White captures Black's pawn. This opens the f-file, so that
later if White were to castle his Rook would also be looking down the file at
the weak spot.} 6... Nxe5 $2 {This is the wrong way for Black to recapture.} (
6... dxe5 {This is a better move. Now White would play} 7. d3 {
with a good position, but Black would not be losing.}) 7. Nxe5 $3 {A brilliant
queen sacrifice! Notice that the Knight also attacks the weak spot at f7 and
controls d7 as well.} 7... Bxd1 {Black can scarcely believe his good fortune
-- he is a whole Queen ahead against the great master Pillsbury!} 8. Bxf7+ $1 {
But now Pillsbury strikes!} 8... Ke7 {This is the only square the King can go
to. Now he has only one flight square, marked in green.} 9. Nd5# {Checkmate!
llsbury forks the King and the flight square, creating a "mating net" -- a
pattern that checkmates the King.} 1-0

