1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 {This is the move that makes this opening a Vienna Game.
White's Knight and pawn press down on the d5 square, making it hard for Black
to play ...d5 now or later since it would just lose a pawn.} 2... Nc6 {
Black could choose to move either one of his Knights or even his Bishop here.
Playing this Knight to c6 is one of the most common moves. Black is, in fact,
doing exactly what White is doing -- he is gripping the d4 square with his
Knight and his pawn so that White will find it hard to push his pawn to d4.} 3.
f4 {White continues with the Vienna plan. The idea here is to distract Black's
pawn so that Black's pieces do not have so much control over the d4 square.   
  This move is a sacrifice. White is offering Black a pawn in order to get
something else in return.} 3... exf4 {Black takes the bait!} 4. Nf3 {The first 
thing White has to do is to bring out this Knight. Black was threatening to
play ...Qh4+, which would be very annoying. But White's Knight on f3 stops
that idea.} 4... Bb4 {Black must have realized that he cannot bring out his
Knight to f6 without getting it chased away.} 5. Nd5 $1 {Normally, White would
not want to move this piece twice in the opening. But in this case, the move
is a fork: it attacks both b4 and f4. The Bishop on b4 is defended, but Black
does not want to give it up for a Knight. Even though Knights and Bishops are
usually worth about the same number of points, a Bishop is sometimes a little
bit better, especially when the center is open and some pawns have been traded
off.} 5... Ba5 {Black backs away, avoiding the exchange on b4. And his Bishop
also pins White's d-pawn, preventing White from playing the move d4. But of
course, this leaves the pawn on f4 free for the taking.} 6. Nxf4 {
White snips off the pawn.} 6... d6 {Black moves this pawn up as far as he
dares. Of course he cannot put it on d5 -- White controls that square.} 7. c3 {
White wants to play d4, but this is not possible unless he breaks the pin on
his d-pawn. This move breaks the pin. White is threatening to play d4 now when
his fine center will give him the advantage.} 7... Bg4 {Black brings out
another piece and pins White's Knight against the Queen. Pins against the
Queen are tricky; sometimes they work, but sometimes they turn out not to work
at all.} 8. Bb5 $5 {This is an interesting move. White pins the Knight on c6,
and this sets up some threats. White now threatens to play d4 and then d5, for
example, winning material on c6 because the Knight is pinned.} (8. d4 {
This is also a very good move, taking space in the center and preparing to
play Bd3 and 0-0.}) 8... Kf8 {Black does not like the pin, so he moves his
King sideways in order to get out of the pin. Now his Knight is free to move.
But his King is not able to castle -- once you have moved your King, you
cannot castle in that game.} 9. O-O $1 {White quickly castles. This puts his
Rook on the same file as Black's King. Right now it looks as though there are
many pieces between the Rook and the King. But keep watching!} 9... Ne5 $2 {
Black thinks that he can exchange some pieces with a tactic. He notices that
White's Knight is pinned to his Queen, so he thinks that by moving his own
Knight up he can trade some pieces at f3.     But he gets a bigsurprise!} 10.
Nxe5 $3 {This is a wonderful sacrifice! White is willing to give up his Queen,
but he will win Black's King for it!} 10... Bxd1 {Black takes the Queen --
what else would he do? He does not see what is happening to him here.} 11.
Neg6+ {An amazing check! Black can take White's Knight two different ways --
with pawns! But if you look closely, you will see that White's Rook is still
looking at  Black's King through those pieces on the f-file...} 11... fxg6 {
... and now there is only the Knight between the Rook and the King. So ...} (
11... hxg6 12. Nxg6#) 12. Nxg6# {Black's King is caught in the double check,
and White's pieces control all of the empty squares around him. What a
wonderful sacrifice!} 1-0

[Event "?"]
