[Date "1876.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chigorin, Mikhail I"]
[Black "Solovtsov, A V."]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C25"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2007"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[EventDate "1876.??.??"]
[Source "Pickard & Son"]
[SourceDate "2001.06.15"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4 {This isn't a Vienna game -- yet. When White moves his pawn to
f4 on the second move like this, he is playing the King's Gambit. But after
next move we will be back in a Vienna.} 2... exf4 3. Nc3 {
With this move, White invites Black to transpose back into the Vienna Game.} (
3. Nf3 {This is the normal King's Gambit move. One of the reasons that it is
less popular today than it was when Chigorin played this game is that Black
can reply with} 3... d5 4. exd5 Nf6 {when White cannot make a big center.})
3... Nc6 {Now we reach a Vienna by transposition of moves.} (3... Qh4+ {
This is one of the reasons that White usually does not use this order of moves.
Because he has not yet developed his Knight to f3, White must meet this check
by moving his King.After} 4. Ke2 {
it is difficult for White to find a safe spot for his King, who cannot castle.}
) 4. Nf3 {White's Knight comes up to the perfect square, and now Black has no
chance to make an obnoxious Queen check at h4.} 4... g5 {This move is greedy.
Black is one pawn ahead and he wants to keep it. But this move does not help
him to control the center and does not develop any pieces.} 5. d4 {
White continues to concentrate on making good moves.} 5... g4 {
Very greedy! Black tries to frighten White's Knight into moving away.} (5... d6
{is better, but we will see in other games that White has a very good response
in} 6. d5 $1 Ne5 7. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 8. Bxd7+ $1 {
when each way of recapturing causes Black problems.}) 6. Bc4 $5 {White offers
a piece sacrifice in the opening.    This is a very daring thing to do. If
White cannot create a strong attack with his lead in development, Black will
catch up in developing his pieces -- and then White will simply be a full
piece down. So if this move doesn't win, it probably loses!    Still, it is
very difficult for Black to defend against the strong attack that White now
creates.} 6... gxf3 {Black may as well take this piece since he cannot get any
advantage by refusing to take it.} (6... Bg7 7. Bxf4 gxf3 8. Qxf3 Nxd4 9. Bxf7+
Kxf7 10. Qh5+ Kf8 11. O-O Nf6 12. Be5 Nxc2 13. Nd5 $18) 7. Qxf3 Nxd4 8. Bxf7+ {
White gives up a second piece in order to pull Black's King out into the
middle of the board.} 8... Kxf7 9. Qh5+ {
With this check White gets his Queen away from Black's Knight.} 9... Kg7 (9...
Ke6 10. Qd5+ Ke7 11. Qe5+ (11. Qxd4 Nf6 12. Nd5+ Kf7 13. Bxf4) 11... Ne6 12.
Qxh8) 10. O-O {Castling is an attacking move here: it brings a Rook to an open
file. Watch how this Rook helps in the attack now!} 10... Ne6 {
Black brings his Knight backward in order to help defend his pawn on f4.} 11.
Bxf4 {White has two attackers on the pawn, so he can afford to take twice.}
11... Nxf4 {Black tries to exchange as many pieces off as possible.} (11... Nf6
12. Be5 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Rf8 14. Nd5 Be7 15. Nxf6 Bxf6 16. Rxf6 Rxf6 17. Rf1 Kg8
18. Bxf6 Qf8 19. Rf3 $18) 12. Rxf4 {Now the Rook joins in the attack and
clears the f1 square so that the other Rook can come to the f-file too.    
 White threatens 13.Rf7#} 12... Nh6 {
Black defends the f7 square so that White does not have a checkmate there.} 13.
Raf1 {White brings his other Rook into the attack. Without this piece, there
would be no way for White to force a win.} 13... Be7 {Black wants to play ...
Rf8. This would fight back against White's Rooks on the f-file and would
create a hiding place for his King on h8.} 14. Qe5+ Kg6 15. Nd5 $1 {White's Kni
ght, too, joins in the attack. Black cannot defend himself now against all of
the threats.} 15... Bg5 16. Rf6+ $1 {A final sacrifice!} (16. Rf6+ Bxf6 17.
Rxf6+ Kg7 18. Qg5#) 1-0

