1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 exf4 4. Nf3 d6 5. d4 g5 {This is a common line with
stronger players. You should study White's next few moves carefully.} 6. d5 $1
Ne5 7. Bb5+ $1 {This is a very annoying check.} 7... c6 (7... Bd7 {
looks natural, but look more closely:} 8. Bxd7+ Nxd7 9. Qd4 $1 f6 10. h4 $1 g4
11. Ng5 $1 fxg5 12. Qxh8 $18) 8. dxc6 bxc6 9. Nxe5 $1 dxe5 $2 {
This loses outright.} (9... cxb5 10. Qd5 $1 dxe5 {
and now White picks up a few pawns on the way to winning the Rook on h8:} 11.
Qxb5+ $1 Bd7 12. Qxe5+ $1 Qe7 13. Qxh8 $16) 10. Bxc6+ $1 Bd7 {Now White could
just take the Rook on a8, but there is something even more embarrassing for
Black.} 11. Qd5 $1 Rc8 (11... Bxc6 $4 12. Qxc6+ Ke7 13. Nd5+ $18) 12. Qxe5+ Qe7
13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Qb5+ (14. Qxh8 Nf6 15. O-O $18) 14... Kd8 15. Bxf4 $1 (15.
Bxf4 gxf4 16. O-O-O+ Kc7 17. Nd5+ $18) 1-0

