[SourceDate "2003.11.25"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {One of the nice things about having the Vienna in your
repertoire is that you can use this sideline against Alekhine's Defense.} 2...
e5 {Now we are back in the Vienna.} (2... d5 3. e5 {is a good line for White,
though you should study it a bit before going into it.}) 3. f4 Bb4 {This is a s
ort of reversed Ruy Lopez, Schliemann Defense, where White has an extra tempo.
Since the Schliemann is a very dangerous defense even with Black, it must be
even better here with White.} 4. fxe5 $1 Bxc3 5. dxc3 $1 {
This capture is important, for a reason we will see shortly.} 5... Nxe4 6. Qg4
$1 {The point: White has a fork here, and Black cannot meet the fork with ...
Ng5 because White's Bishop is controlling that square. (Thank you, dxc3!)} 6...
d5 7. Qxg7 Ke7 8. Nf3 {
This move is fine, but White has several other good options.} (8. c4) (8. Qh6)
8... Qf8 9. Qxf8+ Rxf8 10. Ng5 Nxg5 11. Bxg5+ Ke6 12. Bd3 Kxe5 {
Oops! That was too much to eat for lunch.} (12... Rg8 {
would have been wiser, though after} 13. Bf6 Nd7 14. O-O {
White remains much, much better.}) 13. O-O f5 14. Rae1+ Kd6 15. Be7+ 1-0

