1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 exf4 {This move is a mistake that many players make.
White's pawn can attack the Black Knight now.} 4. e5 $1 {The poor Knight has
almost no safe squares to go to! Only g8 -- back where he came from -- would
be safe.} 4... Qe7 {Black tries to keep his Knight where it is by pinning
White's pawn against his King. Black also threatens just to take the pawn with
his Queen, which would be check.} 5. Qe2 $1 {White breaks the pin by putting
another piece between his King and Black's Queen. By putting the Queen here,
White also defends the pawn. And the Queen is also on the same open file as
Black's King. Right now that doesn't seem too important as there are some
other things in the way. But keep watching!    Now Black's Knight is once
again attacked by the pawn, and this time he must go back home.} 5... Ng8 6.
Nf3 {White brings out his other Knight before trying to attack anything. It is
almost always a good idea to get out some pieces before you try to do anything
tricky!} 6... Nc6 {Black also brings out a Knight, the only one that he can
bring out to a good square.} 7. d4 {This move is the one White wants to play
in the Vienna. Black's pawn has been pulled away from e5 to f4, so White has
enough control of the middle of the board to make a big pawn center. White is
also threatening to develop another piece with the capture 8.Bxf4.} 7... d6 $4
{Black tries to attack White's big center with a pawn. This would be a good
idea in most cases, but here White's Queen is on the same file as Black's King,
and by playing ...d6 Black has given White a chance to trade pawns. If only
Black's Queen were not on the e-file, that pawn trade would be check! This
gives White a very good idea.} 8. Nd5 $1 {
White's Knight leaps forward and chases Black's Queen away.} 8... Qd8 {
By putting his Queen here, Black keeps from losing her to a fork. But now
White has a very clever way of using the position of his Queen and Black'sKing.
} (8... Qe6 {This move would keep the Queen on the e-file, but there is a
terrible problem with it. Can you see White's tactic?} 9. Nxc7+ $1 {
This fork wins Black's Queen.}) 9. Nxc7+ $1 {This is a Knight fork, attacking
Black's King and Rook. Black looked at this position and then, realizing that
he was lost, resigned! Do you see why?} ({After} 9. Nxc7+ {
Black would normally play} 9... Qxc7 {But now the Queen is on just the wrong
square. White opens up the e-file for a discovered check with} 10. exd6+ $1 {
and Black's Queen is attacked at the same time that his King is in check!
Black can block the check with his Queen, but that doesn't save her:after}
10... Qe7 {White just plays} 11. dxe7 {
when he has won the Queen for a Knight and should win easily.}) 1-0

