1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 exf4 4. e5 {White chases Black's poor Knight.} 4...
Qe7 {Black tries to use a pin to keep his Knight on this good square. If White
is not careful now Black will just take the pawn on e5.} 5. Qe2 $1 {
White breaks the pin and defends his e-pawn.} 5... Ng8 {
There was nowhere else to go.} 6. Nf3 $1 {White brings out his Knight to a
good square, preventing Black from playing ...Qh4+.} 6... Nc6 {Black develops
another piece, but White's pawns and pieces control the center, and this is
the most important feature of the position.} 7. d4 {White's pawns dominate the
center. Now he has many good ideas, including 8.Bxf4 and 8.Nd5.} 7... d6 {
Black is trying to get rid of White's strong pawn on e5. But White's pieces
are too active.} 8. Nd5 $1 {This pushes Black's Queen away from the e-file so
that White can give a discovered check.} 8... Qd7 9. exd6+ $1 {Check!} 9... Kd8
{Black moves his King to avoid losing a piece on the e7 square.} 10. dxc7+ $1 {
Black's King is caught in a net. The only way he can get out of check is to
give up his Queen. So Black resigns.} 1-0

