1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 exf4 4. e5 Qe7 5. Qe2 f3 $2 {
This move does nothing for Black, yet it seems to be played rather often.} 6.
Nxf3 Nh5 7. d4 {Quite strong, if not absolutely the sharpest move available.} (
7. Nd5 Qd8 8. g4 c6 9. Nf6+ Nxf6 10. exf6+ Be7 11. fxe7 $18) 7... g6 $2 {
This defends the Knight on h5, but it fatally weakens the dark squares.} 8. Nd5
$1 Qd8 9. Bg5 $1 f6 10. exf6+ Kf7 11. Ne5+ {Black, who must have been
thoroughly disgusted with his position, resigned at this point.} (11. Ne5+ Ke6
(11... Kg8 12. f7+ {is the simplest win} (12. Qc4 {
forces mate but requires a bit of lookahead.})) 12. Nc6+ Kxd5 {and White can
either take the Queen (advisable for a young player in a real game) or force
mate in three with} 13. Qc4+ Kd6 14. Qc5+ Ke6 15. Nxd8#) 1-0

