1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 exf4 4. e5 Qe7 5. Qe2 $1 Ng8 6. Nf3 b6 {
Better than ...d6 or ...f6, either of which could be met by Nd5.} 7. d4 Bb7 8.
Bxf4 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qb4 $4 {
This is a severely misguided attempt to find counterplay.} 10. Qxa8 {
Of course. White will get huge amounts of material along the back row.} (10. a3
{is another way to win, because of the amusing trap} 10... Qxb2 11. Ra2 $1 $18
{and Black loses his Queen -- !}) 10... Qxb2 11. Qxb8+ Ke7 12. Nd5+ Ke6 13.
Nxc7+ ({Or} 13. Qe8+ Kxd5 14. Qxd7+ Bd6 15. c4+ Kxd4 16. Rd1+ Kc5 17. Rd5+ Kb4
18. Rb5+) 13... Kf5 14. Rd1 (14. Bd3+ Kxf4 15. O-O+ (15. Qxf8 Qxa1+ 16. Ke2
Qxh1 17. Nd5+ Kg4 18. Qxg7+ Kh4 19. Ne3 $18 {and Black cannot stop mate.})
15... Kg5 16. Qxf8) 14... Qxc2 15. Bd3+ 1-0

