[SourceDate "2001.06.15"]

{In this game both players use the tactical idea of pinning pieces and pawns.
But in the end, White's tactics are stronger.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 {
This Knight move makes the opening a Vienna Game.} 2... Nc6 {
Black copies White's move.} 3. f4 {This is the Vienna Gambit. White offers a
pawn sacrifice in order to gain greater control of the center.} 3... Nf6 $2 {
This move brings out a piece to a good square, which is usually a good thing
to do in the opening. But this is not an ordinary position; White is able to
chase Black's Knights all over the board.} 4. fxe5 $1 {
First, White takes away Black's pawn from the center.} 4... Nxe5 {Black has to
take back, or else his Knight on f6 must retreat and he has simply lost a pawn.
} 5. d4 $1 {Now White has made a perfect center. Meanwhile, Black is moving
the same piece over and over again, trying to get to a safe square.} 5... Ng6
6. e5 $1 {The pawns are incredibly strong! Now Black must send this Knight
back where he came from.} 6... Ng8 {There was nowhere else to go.} 7. Nf3 {
It is usually a good idea to bring out your Knights early. Here, White's
Knight cannot be chased away by pawns because it is White, not Black, who
controls the center.} 7... d5 {Finally, Black gets a pawn of his own in the
center. It's a little late, but better late than never!} 8. Bd3 {White continue
s to bring out his minor pieces -- Knights and Bishops -- quickly. Now he is
ready to castle.} 8... Bb4 {Black is also getting his pieces out now. With
this move he pins White's Knight.} 9. O-O {By castling, White breaks the pin.
Castling also puts White's Rook on the open f-file where it is well posted. We
will see in a few more moves that this Rook becomes very active on the f7
square.} 9... Be6 {Black brings out another piece.} 10. Ng5 $1 {White's Knight
takes aim at Black's Bishop on e6. Black cannot play ...h6 now to push the
Knight away or he will lose a piece.} 10... N8e7 {
Black brings this Knight back out to defend his Knight on g6 another time.} (
10... h6 $4 11. Nxe6 $1 {Black's pawn on f7 has two jobs to do, defending both
the e6 square and the Knight on g6. Unfortunately, he cannot do both jobs at
once.} 11... fxe6 12. Bxg6+ $18 {White has won a piece and Black's King must
start wandering. White should win easily.}) 11. Nxe6 {
White goes ahead and takes the Bishop. This will create a weak pawn at e6.}
11... fxe6 {
Black has no choice -- he cannot let White take a piece for nothing.} 12. Qg4 {
White sees the weak pawn at e6 and attacks it, bringing his Queen out with a
threat.} 12... Qd7 {Black must defend the weak pawn.} 13. Bg5 {
White brings out another piece.} 13... O-O-O {Since Black cannot castle on the
kingside, he castles queenside instead. But notice that now Black's Knight on
e7 is pinned to his Rook on d8.} 14. Rf7 {Since Black's King is no longer on
e8, Black does not control the f7 square. White uses this fact to send his
Rook deep into Black's side of the board where it attacks the weak pawn on g7
and pins Black's Knight a second time from a different direction.} 14... Rde8 {
Black adds another guard to his Knight. Surprisingly, he needs it! He also
unpins the Knight in one direction.} ({We can see White's plan in action if
Black tries to ignore White's last move with something like} 14... Kb8 {
Now White can win material because Black's Knight on e7 is not defended enough
times! "Not defended enough times?" you ask. "It is defended three times!" Yes,
but watch how White removes two of those defenders:} 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. a3 Bxc3
17. Rxe7 $1 {A Zwischenzug -- an "in between" move!} 17... Qc6 18. bxc3 Qxc3
19. Rd1 $18 {White has won a Bishop for a pawn and has a winning position.})
15. Ne2 {White sees that Black's Bishop on b4 does not have many squares to go
to. He wants to chase it away so that the Knight on e7 will have fewer
defenders, but he does not want Black to be able to reply by taking White's
Knight on c3. So he brings the Knight back, preparing to play c3 and b4
attacking the Bishop.} 15... Qc6 {Black unpins his Knight on e7 by moving his
Queen out of the line of White's Rook. Now the Knight is not pinned at all.
Notice that Black's Queen still defends the pawn on e6 from the side.} 16. c3 {
White begins to push back Black's Bishop.} 16... Ba5 {
There is no other safe place to go.} 17. a4 $1 {White's queenside pawns are
threatening to come forward now and trap Black's Bishop. Even more importantly,
Black's Queen may be trapped as well.} 17... Qb6 {Black sets up a pin on the
pawn at d4. This pawn has a job already defending the pawn on e5. So now Black
is threatening to take that pawn.} 18. b4 {Black's Bishop, however, has
nowhere to go. So White traps it by rolling forward with his queenside pawns.}
18... Bxb4 $5 {Since the Bishop cannot escape, Black grabs a pawn for it and
gets ready to try to win the e-pawn and, he thinks, more than just that.} 19.
cxb4 {White needs to take this Bishop before it becomes dangerous. But has
White overlooked Black's idea?} 19... Nxe5 {This looks like a winning move,
forking White's Queen and Rook because White's pawn on d4 is pinned and cannot
take the Knight.} 20. a5 $1 {White counterattacks! Black's Queen is now under
attack and he must move her or lose another piece.} 20... Qxb4 $5 {It looks lik
e Black has found a good reply, pinning the d-pawn a different way -- this
time against White's undefended Queen. But White has the perfect reply.} ({
Black is already one piece down and cannot afford to trade Queens. If he does,
this is what might happen:} 20... Nxg4 21. axb6 {Naturally White takes Black's
Queen. But now White is threatening to play 22.bxa7 and make a new Queen on
a8!} 21... axb6 {Black stops that threat by taking the pawn. Now, however,
White can win a second piece.} 22. Bxe7 $18 {
White has two Bishops for some pawns and should win the game easily.}) 21.
Qxe6+ $1 {By moving away from the 6th rank, Black's Queen left the pawn on e6
undefended. Now White takes it with check and Black's position falls apart.}
21... Nd7 {Unfortunately, Black has no time to take White's Rook since the
rules of chess force him to get out of check.} 22. Rb1 (22. Bxe7 {
is also very strong.}) 22... Qa3 23. Bf5 {One final deadly pin! Black cannot
use either his Queen or his Rook to defend the Knight on d7 without losing the
Knight on e7.} 1-0

