1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 Nc6 $2 {Good players have been collecting points for
years against inexperienced players who make this natural move.} 4. fxe5 Nxe5
5. d4 Nc6 {Better than 5...Ng6, which is often seen. But either way, Black is
in bad shape.} 6. e5 Qe7 7. Be2 {A simple move. White must leave the Queen on
d1 in order to keep defending the pawn at d4.} (7. Kf2 $5 Ng8 8. Nf3 {
is also strong.}) 7... Ng8 8. Nf3 b6 9. O-O h6 10. Bf4 {This looks like a
random developing move, but it is not. The Bishop is on f4 for a reason.} 10...
Bb7 {Black is one move away from castling queenside, when he can hope to
survive some distance into the middlegame.} 11. Nd5 $1 Qd8 12. e6 $3 d6 13.
exf7+ Kxf7 14. Ng5+ hxg5 15. Bh5+ ({Yes, in case you were wondering,} 15. Bxg5+
{is also good:} 15... Nf6 16. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 17. Bh5+ $1 {
Inviting everyone to the party!} 17... Kg8 (17... Ke6 18. Qg4+ Kxd5 19. Bf7#)
18. Nxf6+ Kg7 19. Qg4+ Kh6 20. Qg6#) 15... Rxh5 16. Qxh5+ Ke6 17. Bxg5 Be7 18.
Qg4+ (18. Qh3+ Kxd5 19. Qb3+ Kxd4 20. Rad1+ Kc5 (20... Ke4 21. Qe3#) 21. Rd5#)
18... Kxd5 19. Qf3+ (19. Qf3+ Ke6 20. Qf5#) 1-0

