1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 Nc6 {There's that error again!} 4. fxe5 Nxe5 5. d4 {
Now the Knights get kicked all over the board.} 5... Ng6 (5... Nc6 6. e5 Qe7 {
Now White can't play 7.Qe2 because the d-pawn hangs, but he does have an
interesting and somewhat startling possibility here:} 7. Kf2 $5 {The King is
quite safe here, and now Black must lose time retreating his Knight, so
White's pieces come out very quickly.} (7. Bg5 {
is also good, for those who fear moving the King so early!}) 7... Ng8 (7... Nd5
8. Nxd5 Qh4+ 9. g3 Qe4 10. Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 Qxh1 12. Nf3 d5 13. Qd3 {
and White threatens 14.Bg2 trapping and winning Black's Queen.}) 8. Nf3 d6 9.
Bb5 dxe5 10. Re1 $1 a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Nxe5) 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 $1 {This is us
ually the best way to meet a Queen pin up the file. White is not seriously
inconvenienced since he can castle queenside quickly. The important tactical
point of having a Queen on e2 will show up in a couple of moves.} 7... Ng8 8.
Nf3 d6 $4 {Black has no good way to free himself, but this natural-looking
move is a disaster.} (8... f6 {also walks into} 9. Nd5 $1 Qd8 (9... Qf7 10.
Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 $18) 10. exf6+ $1 {
when Black must give up at least a piece because} 10... Kf7 {allows} 11. Ng5#)
9. Nd5 $1 Qe6 (9... Qd7 10. Nxc7+ $1 Qxc7 11. exd6+ $18) 10. Nxc7+ 1-0

