1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 Nc6 4. fxe5 Nxe5 5. d4 Nc6 6. e5 Ng8 7. Nf3 d6 {
This is relatively best. Black hopes to chip away at White's center. You need
to memorize the following play since it shows how White should take advantage
of this plan.} 8. Bb5 $1 {
Step #1: White pins the Knight, reducing the pressure against e5.} 8... Bd7 {
Breaking the pin. But now White is ready to castle, which changes things
because he will have pressure against f7.} (8... Bg4 {
can be met in several good ways, one of which is} 9. d5 a6 10. dxc6 axb5 11.
cxb7 Rb8 12. O-O {and Black has difficulties, e.g.} 12... Rxb7 (12... dxe5 13.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 (13... Kxd8 14. Nxe5) 14. Nxe5 $18) (12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qd7 14. e6
$1 Qxe6 (14... fxe6 $4 15. Qxf8#) 15. Nxb5 Qd7 16. Be3 Qxb5 17. Qxf7+ Kd8 18.
Qxf8+ $18) 13. Qd5 Qc8 14. exd6 Bxd6 15. Ng5 Be6 16. Nxe6 fxe6 (16... Qxe6 $4
17. Qxb7 $18) 17. Qc6+ Ke7 18. Bg5+ Nf6 19. Ne4 $18) 9. O-O $1 h6 {Black is try
ing to keep a White Knight out of g5. But that wasn't the main worry.} (9...
dxe5 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Nxe5 $1 Nf6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Qd3 O-O 15.
Rae1 $16 {White has better prospects in both the middlegame and the endgame
thanks to his more active pieces and better pawn structure.}) 10. Bc4 $1 {
Now the f7 square is very sensitive.} 10... Nge7 {Missing the point.} 11. Ng5
$3 {Ouch!!} 11... d5 (11... hxg5 12. Bxf7#) 12. Nxf7 (12. Nxf7 Qc8 13. Nxh8
dxc4 14. Qh5+ Kd8 15. Rxf8+ Be8 16. Qxe8#) 1-0

