1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 Nc6 $2 {Why are there so many games in this file
with this inferior move? Partly just to drill into you the fact that it is
played often, so you must know how to punish it!} 4. fxe5 Nxe5 5. d4 $1 Ng6 6.
e5 $1 Ng8 7. Nf3 c5 {Black wants to break up White's strong pawn center. By
itself this is a reasonable goal, but he is losing too much time trying to do
it.} (7... d6 {is more reasonable, but White has a strong attack if he just
develops with all possible speed, e.g.} 8. Bc4 $1 dxe5 9. O-O $1 {and now} 9...
exd4 $2 {loses to} 10. Ng5 $1 {
since Black cannot take the Knight without getting mated:} 10... dxc3 11. Bxf7+
Ke7 12. Re1+ Kf6 13. Qf3+ Nf4 14. Qxf4+ Bf5 15. Qe5#) 8. Bc4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 {
It is perfectly fine to have your Queen in the center if the opponent has no
way to attack her.} 9... N8e7 (9... b6 {
is a silly trap, hoping that White will castle and allow ...Bc5. But} 10. Qd5
$1 {gets the Queen in on f7, after which Black will wish he hadn't been quite
so silly.}) 10. Ng5 {Now there is no good way to defend the f7 square.} 10...
Qa5 {This allows an amusing mate.} (10... f6 $4 11. Bf7#) 11. Bxf7+ Kd8 12.
Ne6# 1-0

