[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C29"]
[WhiteElo "2345"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2007"]
[PlyCount "35"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. d3 {Simplifying his
life: White forces the Knight out and heads for positions similar to those in
the Oxford Variation.} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 Be7 8. d4 Nc6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O {
White has achieved an ideal setup. Given another move or two he will play Bf4
and Qe1-g3 and the Kingside attack will begin in earnest. Black therefore
chops away at e5 while he still has a chance.} 10... f6 $1 {White cannot
support e5 sufficiently with pieces to maintain an outpost there after the
exchanges, because Black can always throw in an exchange on f3 getting rid of
the Knight with a gain of time thanks to the attack on White's Queen. White
therefore trades pawns and seeks play in the resulting semi-symmetrical
positions.} 11. exf6 $1 Bxf6 12. h3 Be6 (12... Bxf3 {
would, of course, be met by} 13. Rxf3 $1 $14 {
rather than by the ... other capture.}) 13. Qe1 $1 {The standard maneuver: the
Queen heads for g3. Black's Bishop on f6 is not exactly badly placed, but its
only real role is defense: it is not creating any serious threats.} 13... Re8
14. Qg3 Kh8 {White's judgment is vindicated. His Bishops are more actively
posted than Black's, and his Queen is participating on the Kingside in a
significant way. He now pursues these advantages with great energy.} 15. Ng5 $5
({It is even stronger to toss in} 15. Rb1 {
first, getting the Rook off of the dark diagonal. Then} 15... b6 16. Ng5 {
leads to positions similar to those we get in the game, but with fewer options
for Black.}) 15... Bg8 (15... h6 16. Nxe6 Rxe6 17. Rb1 Rb8 18. Bf5 Re8 19. Qg6
$1 $18 {and Black is toast.}) 16. Bxh7 $1 {Very alert tactics from White!
Black's Bishop on g8 is overloaded defending both h7 and f7 (against the fork
threat).} 16... Bxg5 (16... Bxh7 17. Nf7+ $18 {
picks up the Queen for two minor pieces.}) 17. Bxg5 {The point: White
recaptures with a strike at the Black Queen, so there is no time to regain the
lost h-pawn. Even more than the material loss, the lack of cover for the Black
King is now decisive.} 17... Qd6 18. Bf4 {Black is losing more material
because of threats of moving the B/h7 and checking on h4.} 1-0

[Event "Berlin CC"]
