1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Be7 6. d3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 Nc6 8.
d4 Be6 9. Bd3 h6 {Black has probably seen enough Kingside attacks in the
Vienna to have a hearty dislike of getting mauled in that sector of the board.
Here he prepares an unusual idea: to whisk the King to the Queenside.} 10. O-O
Qd7 11. a4 $1 {White recognizes that Black is planning to put his Monarch on
the western half of the board and he immediately plays to gain space there and,
potentially, to use this pawn as a battering ram.} 11... Na5 12. Nd2 {
If Black were to castle Kingside, the pawn on h6 would cry out for sacrifices
which White could prepare at leisure. White therefore doesn't worry about
moving his Knight "away." Besides, Black has already made it clear that he
will not be castling Kingside.} 12... O-O-O 13. Nb3 Nc4 14. a5 {The Black Knigh
t now runs short of squares. In addition, this pawn may be used as a battering
ram later with a6.} 14... f5 15. Qe2 {Increasing pressure on the Knight.} 15...
g5 16. Nd2 $1 {More pressure on the Knight! Once the blockade is lifted from
the c4 square, Black will face many additional problems.} 16... Nxd2 17. Bxd2
f4 {Black's Kingside pawns make a curious impression. If White had pieces on
the Kingside, paradoxically, he would stand worse! But as matters stand the
pawns attack nothing and White has just enough time to beat his opponent to
the attack.} 18. Rfb1 $1 Bg4 19. Qf1 {For reasons that will become obvious in
one more move, White wants to keep his Queen on this diagonal.} 19... Rdf8 20.
Ba6 $1 {Now it's a question of whose attack comes first. White, with an open
file, is the odds-on favorite.} 20... Qf5 (20... bxa6 21. Qxa6+ Kd8 22. Rb8+
$18 {wins Black's Queen.}) 21. Rxb7 $1 {Setting up a discovery.} 21... Kd7 22.
Qb5+ Ke6 23. Rxc7 {Black's King is doing an amazing levitation act, but he's
going to come crashing down.} 23... Rd8 24. c4 (24. Qb7 Rhe8 25. Rc6+ Kf7 26.
Rf6+ $18 {is also very convincing.}) 24... Qe4 25. Qc6+ Kf5 {
Further toward the front!} 26. c3 {
No need to let Black have the d-pawn with check.} 26... Qe2 27. cxd5 Qxd2 28.
Qe6+ Ke4 29. Qxg4 {
Faced with the threat of 30.Qf3+ Kf5 31.Bd3+, Black finally calls it a day.} (
29. Qxg4 Kxd5 30. Bb7#) 1-0

