1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3 (5. Nf3 {is the move I am
recommending in this repertoire file, but because Black reacts fairly
passively it will come to the same thing.}) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Be7 7. Nf3 {
By transposition we have arrived at the main line.} 7... O-O 8. d4 c6 $6 {
This "solid" move does not meet the demands of the position. Black apparently
does not realize that he is going to be attacked on the Kingside, where
White's pawns are pointing.} 9. Bd3 {
White's pieces come naturally to excellent squares.} 9... Be6 10. h4 $6 {
This really does telegraph White's intentions. 10.0-0 is a simpler way to
handle the position, but in the game Black fails spectacularly to cope with
White's idea.} 10... Bg4 $2 (10... f6 $1 {would be very well timed here since
White has weakened his Kingside without making a purposeful move.}) 11. Bxh7+
$1 {Well, wasn't that the plan?} 11... Kxh7 12. Ng5+ Bxg5 13. hxg5+ {
And of course this is check, so Black loses back the piece at g4.} 13... Kg6
14. Qxg4 Rh8 15. Rh6+ $3 {A glorious finish!} (15. Rh6+ gxh6 (15... Rxh6 16.
gxh6+ Kh7 17. Qxg7#) 16. gxh6+ Kh7 17. Qg7#) 1-0

