1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. d3 Nxc3 7. bxc3
d4 8. Be2 {
transposes into the game, and that is the move order I am recommending for you.
}) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 d4 {This is Black's theoretically approved move here.} (
6... Nc6 $5 {Black should play this tricky move, which gives White a chance to
go wrong and risks nothing if White is on his toes.} 7. Nf3 $1 ({
The temptation here is to play} 7. d4 $2 {
immediately, which gives White a poor game after the obnoxious check} 7... Qh4+
$1 8. Ke2 {This is the only move, but it is quite miserable.} (8. Kd2 $4 Nxd4
$1 9. cxd4 Qxd4+ {
and the other Rook falls -- a pleasing symmetry, if you have Black!}) (8. g3 $4
Qe4+ $19 {and Black wins a Rook.} 9. Qe2 (9. Kf2 Qxh1 10. Nf3 Bh3 $19) 9...
Qxh1 {Now White can make only feeble attempts to trap the Queen, e.g.} 10. Qf2
(10. Nf3 Bg4 $19 {and Black forces off Queens.} (10... Bh3 $19 {
is almost as good.})) 10... Qe4+ $19 {and the Queen is out.}) 8... Bg4+ 9. Nf3
f6 10. exf6 O-O-O $1 (10... Qxf6 $17 {
is pleasant for Black but not quite so vicious.}) 11. fxg7 Bxg7 $19 {and with .
..Rhe8 Black will have overwhelming force in the center before White has time
to get his King out of harm's way.}) 7... d4 {
and we have transposed into the game}) 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Be2 Bc5 9. O-O {
With this move White insists on making a sacrifice of the opening.} 9... dxc3+
10. Kh1 O-O 11. Qe1 {
The Queen eyes the pawn on c3, but in most lines she will go to g3.} 11... Nd4
12. Bd1 {The Bishop slips backward to defend c2. This may seem an inglorious
job, and in some sense it is. But it frees White's other pieces for the attack.
} 12... Nxf3 {Black swaps off the Knight that defends e5, but he also gets rid
of his best-centralized piece.} (12... f6 {
is a better way to struggle for the advantage.}) 13. Bxf3 {But now the Bishop
comes back out, putting pressure on b7 and looking to come to e4 and from
there to help in an attack on h7.} 13... Be6 {Black is trying to lure White
into capturing on b7, which would activate Black's Rook.} (13... Re8 {
would also be met by} 14. Qg3 $44) 14. Qg3 {White's Queen often comes to g3 in
the Oxford Variation -- and in the Vienna generally, in fact. Now Bh6 is a
threat, which explains Black's next move.} 14... Kh8 15. Be4 $1 {
Still not tempted by b7! White plays consistently for the attack.} 15... Bd5
16. Bg5 $1 {Now White has both Bishops, Queen, and Rook all participating in
the attack. The results are not pretty for Black.} 16... Qd7 17. Bxh7 $1 Kxh7
18. Bf6 $1 {Only this second sacrifice justifies the first one.} 18... g5 {
Black struggles mightily to confuse the issue, but it's too late.} (18... gxf6
{This leaves the Black King edge-trapped. White takes advantage of this with}
19. Rf4 $1 Be3 20. Rh4+ $1 Bh6 21. Qe3 Bxg2+ {
A last desperate hope that White will let a Rook get to g6.} 22. Kg1 $1 $18) (
18... Rg8 {This leads to a quick and easy mate:} 19. Qh4+ Kg6 20. Qg5+ Kh7 21.
Qh5#) 19. Qxg5 Bxg2+ 20. Qxg2 $1 {
Obviously White does not want to get skewered on the g-file.} 20... Rg8 21.
Qe4+ $1 (21. Qe4+ Rg6 22. Rf5 $18 {answers all questions.}) 1-0

