1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. Qg4 $1 {Rules of thumb have their exceptions,
and this is one of them. Although it is usually a poor idea to move one's
Queen out early in the game, here it is justified because Black has weakened
g7.} 4... Qf6 {This is the most natural-looking way for Black to meet the
threat against g7, and it sets up two threats -- ...d5 and ...Qxf2+. But
White's next move puts a different twist on the position.} (4... d5 $6 {
is bad, but it's not quite as bad as it looks; White needs to play precisely
to keep his loot.} 5. Qxg7 Qf6 6. Qxf6 Nxf6 7. Nxd5 Nxd5 8. exd5 {Black is two
pawns down, but he is better developed and White is weak on c2. Black's only
hope of gaining some counterplay is to hit that weak spot now.} 8... Nd4 (8...
Nb4 9. Bb3) 9. Bd3 $1 {Whichever way Black hits c2, White defends it in with
his Bishop in a way that doesn't allow Black to take the Bishop.} 9... Bf5 10.
Bxf5 Nxf5 11. g4 $1 Nd4 12. Kd1) (4... Kf8 {Now that g7 is defended, White's
first task is to do something against the threat of ...d5.} 5. Qg3 {
This discourages, but does not absolutely prevent, 5...Nd4.} 5... Nf6 6. Nge2 {
Now ...Nd4 can be met by a swap.} 6... d6 7. d3 h6 8. Na4 {
It is desirable for White to snag the Bishop pair.} 8... Bb6 9. Nxb6 axb6 10.
f4 {White has a comfortable game with two Bishops, a safer King, and more
space. He went on to win comfortably in Rogers-Olarasu, Valle d'Aosta 2001.}) (
4... g6 {Here again Black has taken care of the weakness at g7, so White must
deal with the threat of ...d5.} 5. Qg3 {Once again, this is the best retreat,
keeping pressure against e5 to hobble Black's Knight.} 5... d6 6. Nge2 Nf6 7.
d3 h6 8. a3 a6 9. O-O Qe7 10. Kh1 Be6 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 Nd8 13. f4 Nh5 14.
Qf3 f5 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. g4 Ng7 17. gxf5 Nxf5 18. Qg4 Rg8 19. Rxf5 h5 20. Rxh5
{1-0, Najdorf-Dan, San Pablo blindfold simul, 1947.}) (4... Nd4 $5 {is very rar
ely played, but here again White must exercise some care. The right procedure
is} 5. Qxg7 Qf6 {(Other moves lose quickly.)} 6. Qxf6 Nxf6 7. Bd3 {Here the Bis
hop defends both e4 and c2. If Queens were still on the board this would be a
very awkward position for the Bishop, but in this case it is quite all right}
7... Rg8 8. g3 (8. Kf1 c6 9. f4 exf4 10. e5 Ng4 11. Ne4 Be7 12. Nd6+ Bxd6 13.
exd6 $16) 8... b6 9. Nce2 Bb7 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. f3 d5 12. exd5 Bxd5 13. Ne2
Bxf3 14. Rf1 Bxe2 15. Kxe2) 5. Nd5 $1 {
Now Black is forced to take the pawn on f2.} 5... Qxf2+ 6. Kd1 {This is the
critical position. Surprisingly, Black cannot make any further headway on the
kingside; White has all of the critical squares covered. Black, for his part,
is faced with a threat to each of his Rooks: Qxg7 menaces the R/h8, and Nxc7+
threatens to pick up the R/a8. Black's options, therefore, are very limited.}
6... Kf8 {
This is the only way to defend g7 without allowing a checking fork at c7.} 7.
Nh3 $1 {It may seem awkward for the Knight to come out on the rim like this,
but it forces Black's hand since his Queen is suddenly very short of squares.}
7... Qd4 {The most common move -- understandably, since it natural to retreat
the Queen. Now Black threatens to take the Bishop on c4.} ({
This is more or less Black's best chance to bail out with} 7... h5 {
counterattacking on White's Queen.} 8. Qg5 {The best response. Black still has
to figure out what to do about his Queen, and he has no safe way to attack
White's Queen while she stands on g5.} 8... Qd4 (8... f6 9. Qg6 Qh4 10. Nxc7
Qg4+ 11. Qxg4 hxg4 12. Nxa8 gxh3 13. gxh3 Bd6) 9. d3 {Now White threatens c3
trapping the Queen, so Black must immediately strike out at White's Queen.}
9... Be7 {Moving the Bishop not only gains time by attacking White's Queen but
also clears a path back to b6 for Black's Queen to escape from the threat of
c3.} (9... f6 {fails now because White's d-pawn has been moved:} 10. Qg6 Rh6 {
walks into} 11. Bxh6 $18) 10. Nxe7 {Even though Black's Queen has a retreat,
it is still in White's interest to clear his own Queen of attacks and then hit
out at her. White is a pawn down, and gaining breathing space to bring his
Rook into play on f1 is highly desirable.} 10... Ngxe7 11. c3 {This dislocates
Black's Queen a bit, but it is a factor of equal importance that it gives
White's King a rather safe square at c2 so that he can connect his Rooks
rapidly.} 11... Qd6 {keeps the e-pawn defended a bit better, but it does place
the Queen in front of the d-pawn, which gums up Black's already poor
development.} (11... Qb6 12. Rf1 {
This direct threat to f7 severely limits Black's options.} 12... Nd8 (12... f6
$4 13. Rxf6+ $1 $18) 13. Qxe5 {Now White has regained his pawn and has an
excellent game with more central pawns, more space, better piece coordination,
and a safer King.} 13... d6 14. Qf4 f6 15. Kc2 $16) 12. Rf1 f6 (12... Nd8 13.
Kc2 $14) 13. b3 Rh7 14. Qg3 Ke8 15. Kc2 $14) 8. d3 $1 {At a single stroke
Black's game becomes dire. The threat of c3 now hangs over his head, and he
cannot harrass White's Queen for more than about one move. Meanwhile, White
can marshall swift threats against f7 and in some variations sacrifices are
even a legitimate way of crashing through.} 8... Bb6 {
Every road at this point seems to lead directly into a graveyard.} (8... d6 {
White has several ways to win here.} 9. Qh5 (9. Qh4 Bxh3 10. Qxh3 Na5 (10...
Qf2 {was forced, though after} 11. Bd2 {
threatening 12.Be1 White is still much better.}) 11. Rf1 Nxc4 12. Qd7 f6 13.
Nxf6 Qf2 14. Rxf2 Bxf2 15. Nh5 {1-0 Mieses,J-Chigorin,M/Ostend 1906 (15)}) 9...
Bxh3 10. Rf1 $3 {
Threatening mate in one and also taking back control of the f2 square.} 10...
Be6 11. c3 $18 {Black must lose his Queen.}) 9. Rf1 f6 (9... Nd8 10. c3 Qc5 11.
Ng5 Nh6 12. Qh4 d6 {1-0 Alekhine-Lugowski, Belgrade simul, 1931.}) 10. Nxf6 $3
Nxf6 (10... gxf6 11. Bxg8 $1 {Why do something fancy when you can just take
the key defensive piece without any fuss?} 11... Rxg8 12. Rxf6+ {
Black's King is forced forward.} 12... Ke7 13. Qxg8 {Now Black is faced with a
quick mate by the Rook and Queen. He can take the Rook, but ...} 13... Kxf6 14.
Bg5#) 11. Bh6 $3 {1-0, Wundt-Schminke, corr 1989. We can continue the play a
little to see why Black resigned.} (11. Rxf6+ {
also wins, but it is more prosaic:} 11... gxf6 12. Bh6+ Ke8 13. Qg7 d5 14.
Qxh8+ Kd7 15. c3 Qc5 16. exd5 $18) 11... gxh6 12. Rxf6+ Ke8 13. Qg7 d5 14.
Qxh8+ Kd7 15. Bb5 {Now White threatens mate in two with 16.Qg7+, etc.} 15...
Qc5 16. Rf7+ $18 {Black must lose his Queen for the Rook.} 1-0

