1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 $1 {Black should be congratulated on having found
this move, which is more or less the only one that holds out hope of
equalizing. Nevertheless White still has ways to put pressure on Black.} 4.
fxe5 {This pawn at e5 sets the stage for the ensuing struggle. Because of it,
White will have a space advantage for the middlegame. Black must make every
effort to eliminate this pawn, preferably with the "break" ...f6 to liquidate
it. But ...f6 cannot be played too early or Black's King will be exposed. Both
sides can look forward to an interesting struggle!} 4... Nxe4 5. Nf3 {
This is the most popular move for White, though not the sharpest. If you want
to play for blood, you can investigate 5.d3, the Oxford Variation, which leads
to some extremely obscure positions. Even the old Paulsen Variation 5.Qf3!?
has seen some recent action with GM Antal being willing to take the White side
in several tournament encounters. Nevertheless, for simplicity of development
and clarity of plans it is hard to beat 5.Nf3.} ({After} 5. Nf3 {Black has a
bewildering array of choices, and to simplify the learning of the opening I am
recommending a single system for White against most of them. The system
involves 6.d3 to force the Black Knight to capture on c3, followed sooner or
later -- if Black permits it -- by d4 for White.     I admit that this may not
be objectively the best way to play the position. (To be honest, I am unsure.)
But the more testing lines are sometimes counterintuitive and demand greater
precision from White. The system I am recommending has the virtue that it is
very easy to learn and can be played after very little study. It is also, as
the supplemental games will show, played by masters as White, and it is more
than sufficiently dangerous to win real chess games.} 5... Be7 (5... Bc5 $5 {
This is one of the systems where White cannot play d3 -- for obvious reasons,
as the arrival of a Knight on f2 would make White most unhappy! This is also
the line recommended by John Emms in his recent book Play the Open Games as
Black; and though there is no forced advantage for Black, White does have to
play very precisely to avoid getting caught in the tactical meat-grinder.    
Nevertheless, the move loses time since White can lash out at the exposed
Bishop. White should memorize the play in this line since the order of moves
can be important.} 6. d4 {Not subtle. White avoids the labyrinth of
complications arising from 6.Qe2!? when his King ends up on d1 (e.g. after 6...
Bf2+ 7.Kd1 Bb6) and simply grabs more center space.} 6... Bb4 {The natural
reaction, pinning and overloading the White Knight. Sometimes this position
arises by transposition from 5...Be7 and 6...Bb4.} 7. Bd2 (7. Bd3 $6 {
is a spirited sacrifice, but it is almost certainly unsound.}) 7... Nxd2 (7...
Bg4 $5 {is a critical alternative. To avoid the tactical jungle, perhaps
White's best is just} 8. Bb5+ {to rule out ...Nc6, retreating after} 8... c6 {
with} 9. Be2 {Tournament tests of this idea are almost non-existent, but since
Black should play ...c5 it will probably transpose into 7...Bg4 8.Be2 c5,
which is not as dangerous for White as 8...Nc6.} 9... c5 10. a3 Bxc3 11. Bxc3
Nc6 12. O-O {is untested but offers chances for both sides. White will
probably continue with Qe1-g3.}) 8. Qxd2 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 {
See the illustrative game Holubcik-Gregorova.}) (5... Bb4 {This is the other
line that prevents, by force of the threat to the Knight on c3, the immediate
d3. White's plan now is to get castled and put his Queen on e1. From there she
will give latent support to the Knight on c3, and then White can proceed with
d3 evicting Black's strong steed from e4. Black will then lose a tempo because
his Bishop is vulnerable on b4 to a "biff" from a pawn arriving on c3.} 6. Be2
{Modest, but this is all White needs to get castled.} 6... Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8.
Qe1 {All according to plan. Now Black, realizing that d3 cannot be long in
coming, tries to "steal a march" on White by checking immediately when d4 is
not an option.} 8... Bc5+ 9. Kh1 Nxc3 10. bxc3 f6 {So Black has gotten in the
undermining move after all. But he has forgotten that by playing Bc5+
voluntarily, he spared White the trouble of moving the d-pawn twice. White now
lashes out with} 11. d4 $1 Be7 12. Qg3 $1 {reinforcing e5 with pieces and
pawns alike. For an impressive display of White's resources here, see the
illustrative game Leonhardt-De Soyres.}) (5... Nc6 {This move has little
independent significance unless White plays an immediate d4, in which case
Black can gain a whole tempo on the 5...Bc5 lines.  The character of the play
is set by where Black decides to develop his Bishops.} 6. d3 {
The simple plan in action: White forces the trade on c3.} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 d4
{This is Black's theoretically approved move, transposing into the main line
of the Oxford Variation, and it leads to a fascinating struggle.} (7... Bg4 8.
d4 Be7 {But can Black "break" now with} 9. Bd3 f6 {and live to tell the tale?
See the illustrative game Laudati-Roperto to find out.}) 8. Be2 $1 {White makes
a long-term pawn sacrifice, intending to seek compensation through active play
on the kingside.} 8... dxc3 9. O-O Bc5+ 10. Kh1 O-O 11. Qe1 {White's pieces
are more actively placed than they might appear, and Black's castled King will
be a target in the ensuing middlegame. See the game Nunn-Hebden for an
illustration of the dangers Black faces here.}) (5... Bg4 {This allows White
to proceed with the first part of his primary plan, but there is a little
detail arising from the fact that White's control of d4 is reduced.} 6. d3 Nxc3
7. bxc3 Be7 ({What if Black now "wedges" the center with} 7... d4 $5 {
White can play around this pawn with Be2, 0-0, and the omnipresent Vienna
maneuver Qe1-g3. See the illustrative game Sejkora-Morava.}) 8. d4 Nc6 9. Bd3 {
All according to plan. See the illustrative game Mastrovalis-Georgiadis.}) (
5... Nxc3 $6 {White should rejoice if Black plays this move, since now White
will save a whole tempo over lines where he has to play first d3 and only
later d4.} 6. bxc3 Be7 (6... c5 {should also be met by} 7. d4 {
See the illustrative games Pahl-Deiszner and Gerlach-Watson.}) 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3
{White has a very strong position and Black cannot even successfully challenge
e5, since White can reinforce it with Bf4 (preparing to recapture there with
pieces) and castle before Black can bring more pressure to bear on e5. See the
illustrative game Schallop-Gossip. (And bring popcorn: it's a good show!)}) {
Finally we come back to Black's theoretically recommended move, 5...Be7. The
idea behind this move is to challenge White's center -- space is, after all,
White's primary advantage in the Vienna -- with a swift ...f6, supported by
the Bishop at e7. It is a sound plan and leads to an interesting game for both
sides.    Normally White plays 6.d4 and Black bolsters his Knight with ...f5!?,
leading to difficult play. But here too our simple plan can be executed.} 6. d3
{"Inviting" Black's Knight to leave.} 6... Nxc3 {Experience has shown that
Black really should take White's Knight here: there are no good alternatives,
since wandering around with the Knight loses time.} 7. bxc3 {
Capturing toward the center to strengthen it.} 7... O-O ({What if Black
decided that he doesn't want to be mauled on the Kingside? He can prepare
Queenside castling instead with} 7... Nc6 8. d4 Be6 9. Bd3 h6 {But as the
trative game Galego-Bestian shows, the open b-file offers White plenty of play
on that side of the board as well.}) 8. Be2 (8. d4 {White has achieved his
desired pawn formation, though at the cost of a tempo. Black's play now will
determine the further course of the game.} 8... f6 {This is the proper sort of
reaction, but it must be followed up precisely. For proof that it does not
automatically solve all of Black's problems, see the illustrative game
Brechlin-Piontek.} (8... c6 {This move is "solid" but actually poor. White's
attack builds with frightening speed. See the illustrative game Morris-Ennis.})
(8... Bf5 {This move forces White to trade lightsquare Bishops or else deploy
his Bishop more passively at e2. Can White still whip up an attack after the
exchange of the Bishops? For the answer, see the illustrative game
Nilsson-Hansen.}))) *

[Event "SVK-chT3C 0001"]
[Site "SVK"]
[Date "2000.??.??"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Holubcik, Marian"]
[Black "Gregorova, Zuzana"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C29"]
[WhiteElo "2028"]
[BlackElo "2158"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2007"]
[PlyCount "49"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Bc5 {
Forcing White to shift gears and play d4 instead of the intended d3.} 6. d4 Bb4
{Black has deliberately provoked d4 in order to create trouble for White on
the c3 square. White should meet this calmly.} 7. Bd2 {
Breaking the pin makes the most sense.} 7... Nxd2 8. Qxd2 Bf5 9. Bd3 {
A very interesting idea. White plays to prove that the attack can be conducted
without Bishops. Why is this even possible? Because White's primary advantages
here are in Space and Time, and they do not require Bishops for theirexploitati
on.} 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 {Naturally White does not double his pawns.} 10... c6
11. O-O O-O 12. Ne2 $1 {The Knight comes over to the critical sector, the area
of the board where White's pawns are "pointing." There is no sense playing
somewhere else: this is where White *must* play if he is to use the advantage
of space bequeathed upon him by Black's rather tame play.} 12... Na6 $2 {
This Knight will be irrelevant to the further course of the game. At least
with 12...Nd7 Black could have brought it over to aid the King.} 13. c3 Be7 14.
Ng3 {This Knight has a real future at f5. Note the lack of defenders for
various squares in the Black King's field: g7 and h7 are defended only by the
King himself.} 14... Nc7 15. Nf5 f6 16. Rae1 {
Admirable centralization. Warning bells should be going off for Black here.}
16... fxe5 {So White's pawn wedge is eliminated. Should White try to put
another pawn on e5?} 17. Nxe5 $1 {No -- a piece instead! This is a beautiful
illustration of the fact that even when Black gets in ...f6, White is better
if he can finish off the exchanges on e5 by planting a minor piece there on an
outpost square defended by a pawn at d4. Black has nothing comparable to show.}
17... Bf6 18. Qg3 {Arriving by an unusual route. Yet this is very often the
best square for the Queen in the Vienna. Notice that from here the Queen lends
support to e5 as well as keeping pressure on the Black Kingside by watching g7.
} 18... Bxe5 $2 {Tempting as it was to eliminate White's strong Knight, this
move leaves Black defenseless on the dark squares.} 19. Rxe5 $1 {White always
recaptures on e5 with a piece -- a point worth absorbing. Now he threatens
mate on g7, so Black must immediately attend to the threat.} 19... g6 20. Rfe1
{This is adequate, but White misses a killer idea.} (20. Nh6+ $1 {
is immediately crushing:} 20... Kg7 21. Rxf8 Qxf8 (21... Kxf8 22. Rf5+ $3 gxf5
23. Qg8+ Ke7 24. Qf7+ Kd6 25. Nxf5#) 22. Re7+ $3 Qxe7 23. Nf5+ {and White not
only bags the Queen but picks up the Knight on c7 (or keeps his own Knight) in
the bargain.}) 20... Nb5 21. Nh6+ Kh8 22. Re7 {
Now the threat of Qe5+ wraps things up quickly.} 22... Qb8 23. Nf7+ (23. Rxh7+
$1 Kxh7 24. Re7+ Kh8 (24... Kxh6 25. Qh4#) 25. Qh4 $1 $18 {
and White mates quickly.}) 23... Kg8 24. Qh4 Rxf7 25. Rxf7 {
Black is mated in a few moves.} 1-0

[Event "Hilversum"]
[Site "Hilversum"]
[Date "1903.??.??"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Leonhardt, Paul Saladin"]
[Black "De Soyres, John"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C29"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2007"]
[PlyCount "51"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Bb4 {
Like ...Bc5, this move prevents White from carrying out his normal plan of d3.}
6. Be2 {This move does not look very aggressive, and if you are accustomed to
the more exciting lines of the Vienna you might wonder whether White is just
"wimping out" here. Actually, Be2 fits into a plan for White's complete
domination of the center. It is a plan that Black can challenge if he sees it
coming, but even so it is a good and simple plan, and the move Be2 fits into
it perfectly.     The first thing to notice is that the Knight on c3 is in no
immediate danger; it has two sturdy pawns defending it. The problem is that
White wants to play d3, and then there will be only *one* pawn defending c3 --
so White would lose a pawn on that square.     White isn't about to give up
the idea of d3: Black's Knight on e4 is simply too strong and needs to be
challenged. So White's idea is to play Qe1 and only then d3, "biffing" the
Knight. When Black captures on c3 (as he likely will), White will play bxc3
"biffing" the Bishop. So the time White loses playing "quietly" with Be2 will
be partly regained when he drives the Black minor pieces back with these pawn
moves.    But how to get the Queen to e1? White needs to castle to pull this
off, and to castle he must move his Bishop from f1. No other square on the
diagonal is a good one, so Be2 is the indicated move -- all in line with
White's plan!} 6... Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. Qe1 $1 {This is the key move. White has
transferred his Queen to e1 for two reasons. First, as we have already
mentioned, she is helping to reinforce c3 so that the d-pawn is no longer
needed for that purpose. This means that White can now carry on with d3,
kicking Black's Knight out of the center. Second, with the Knight gone,
White's Queen will have access to Kingside squares like g3 from which she can
participate in a Kingside attack.} 8... Bg4 9. d3 Bc5+ 10. Kh1 {Naturally White
does not play d4: Black has two attackers on that square, and in any event
White wants his d-pawn on d3 to kick out the Black Knight.} 10... Nxc3 11. bxc3
{Now White is ready to reinforce his center with d4. Black must act quickly to
contest White's growing spatial advantage.} 11... f6 $1 {A good move that
shows Black has some understanding of the position. Now the fight over e5
becomes intense.} 12. d4 Be7 $1 {Again the best move. Black's Bishop would
have no future on b6, where it "bites on granite" in the form of White's solid
pawn chain. On e7 it helps to support f6 so that, in recapturing on that
square, Black does not expose a Queen or a Rook to attack.} 13. Qg3 $1 {
White rises to the challenge by defending his e-pawn while attacking the Black
Bishop at g4.} 13... Qd7 {Black defends the Bishop and connects his Rooks.
Both players are playing strong moves.} (13... Bxf3 {fails to solve Black's
problems because White has tremendous pressure on the g-file:} 14. Bh6 $1 Rf7
15. Rxf3 $16) 14. Bf4 {White reinforces e5 again. Given two more moves, he
would play Rae1 and Bd3 when he has a virtual stranglehold on the e5 square.}
14... Bxf3 {Black understands that he must not allow White to occupy e5 with a
minor piece, since the "outpost" would be of immense value to White.} 15. Rxf3
fxe5 16. dxe5 {White's pawns are now broken up badly, and any endgame will no
doubt be a trial to him. But on the bright side Black's King is running short
on defenders and the pawn wedge at e5 gives White distinct attacking chances.}
16... Nd8 17. Bd3 {The Bishop finally arrives at its natural square. Black now
has serious difficulties to contend with.} 17... Ne6 18. Qh3 $1 {This clever
move has two purposes. Defensively, it pins the Black Knight to his undefended
Queen so that there is no danger at the moment to White's Bishop at f4.
Offensively, it probes the h7 square so that Black will have to move the pawns
in front of his castled King.} 18... g6 {This gives White a new idea.} 19. c4
$1 {The point of this move is to win the c4 square for the lightsquared Bishop.
Black's Knight on e6 would be forfeit then.} 19... d4 {Black bypasses,
intending to "freeze" White's pawn on the c4 square by playing something -- a
Knight, a Bishop, or even a pawn -- to c5 next turn. Then White's c-pawn
blocks his lightsquared Bishop and is a liability rather than an asset.} 20. c5
$1 {Win the square at any cost!} 20... Nxc5 21. Bc4+ {Finally the Bishop
attains the commanding position White had desired. Note that this is check, so
Black has no time to trade Queens.} 21... Kh8 {The safety of the King here is
only apparent. The g6 push created serious new weaknesses.} 22. Qh6 {
White now threatens e6 and Be5+ as well as simply Rh3.} 22... Rf5 23. Rh3 Rh5 {
Stopping one threat but exposing himself to the other.} 24. e6 $5 {A fancy way
to play the position -- and it does lead to a spectacular finish. But there is
a simpler solution.} (24. Rxh5 gxh5 (24... Bf8 25. Qxg6 Qg7 26. Qf5 {
and White, a Rook up, wins as he pleases.}) 25. e6 $1 $18 {
Black is powerless against the coming Be5+.}) 24... Qd8 ({
The clever point of White's tactic can be seen after} 24... Rxh6 25. exd7 {
and now thanks to the threat of Be5+ Black must give up the exchange, e.g.}
25... g5 26. Rxh6 gxf4 27. Re1 Bd8 28. Bd3 Nxd3 29. cxd3 $18) 25. Rxh5 gxh5 26.
Be5+ {White mates in five now.} ({The variation is quite lovely:} 26. Be5+ Bf6
27. Qxf6+ Qxf6 28. Bxf6+ Kg8 29. e7+ Ne6 30. Bxe6#) 1-0

[Event "Academia Cup op"]
[Site "ITA"]
[Date "1997.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Laudati, A."]
[Black "Roperto, M."]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C29"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2007"]
[PlyCount "63"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 Nc6 $2 4. Nf3 $6 ({
White misses the chance to take a commanding lead here with} 4. fxe5 $1 Nxe5 5.
d4 Nc6 6. e5 Ng8 7. Nf3 $16) 4... d5 5. fxe5 Nxe4 {
Now we have transposed back into the lines normally reached by 3...d5.} 6. d3
Nxc3 7. bxc3 Bg4 (7... d4 {
is more testing, leading to the main lines of the Oxford Variation.}) 8. d4 Be7
9. Bd3 f6 {This is the natural reaction, but White's next move shows that the
timing of this break is a very sensitive thing.} 10. h3 $5 Bxf3 $2 {
Black will regret this hasty capture.} 11. Qxf3 fxe5 $2 12. Qh5+ $1 g6 (12...
Kd7 {is far worse:} 13. Bf5+ Kd6 14. Ba3+ $18 {
and Black must give up a Knight just to stay in the game.}) (12... Kf8 13. O-O+
Bf6 14. dxe5 {forces Black to give up a piece with} 14... Nxe5 15. Qxe5 $18)
13. Bxg6+ $1 hxg6 14. Qxh8+ $1 {Of course White does not go after wild
speculations with Qxg6+; he just takes the material and trades down.} 14... Kd7
15. Qxd8+ {Now White has a pleasant endgame with an extra exchange.} 15... Rxd8
16. dxe5 $1 {It is true that White's pawns are not lovely, but it is even more
important to get rid of Black's pawn before it comes to e4 than to keep
White's own pawn on d4. A protected passed e-pawn might become a real weapon
for Black.} 16... Bh4+ 17. Ke2 {Since the position genuinely is an endgame,
rather than a middlegame, White's King is safe coming toward the center where
it can be useful.} 17... Rf8 18. Rf1 {As White is ahead in material, he would
be very glad to trade pieces -- particularly one of his Rooks for Black's Rook.
} 18... Re8 {Black sensibly avoids the trade, but now we see one of the
reasons why extra material is such an advantage: even when your opponent
avoids trades, you can *offer* trades in order to activate your pieces.} 19.
Rf7+ $1 Kc8 20. Bf4 {In just a few moves White's pieces have come to far
better squares than they had.} 20... Nd8 (20... Nxe5 {is better, but with
every pair of pieces that comes off the board White's material advantage is
worth proportionally more.} 21. Bxe5 Rxe5+ 22. Kf3 $18) 21. Rh7 g5 $2 {
This cuts off Black's retreat.} 22. Bh2 $1 {Now White encircles the Bishop.}
22... Ne6 23. g3 Bxg3 24. Bxg3 {
Black is now a full Rook down. The rest is slaughter.} 24... Nf4+ 25. Bxf4 gxf4
26. Rg1 Rxe5+ 27. Kf3 Re8 28. Rgg7 {Good technique: White plays for domination
of the seventh rank with his Rooks. This brings the game to an abrupt
conclusion.} 28... c6 29. Rc7+ $1 {
Forcing him to b8 so that everything happens with check.} 29... Kb8 30. Rxb7+
Ka8 31. Rxa7+ Kb8 32. Rhb7+ {Next White will trade Rooks by 32...Kc8 33.Ra8+!
Kxb7 34.Rxe8 when he wins effortlessly.} 1-0

[Event "Iwex Cup"]
[Site "Pardubice"]
[Date "1993.??.??"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Sejkora, Vlastimil"]
[Black "Morava, T."]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C29"]
