1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Nxc3 $2 {
Oh the joys of having a cooperative opponent!} 6. bxc3 c5 7. d4 {
Of course White creates a big center for free.} 7... Bf5 8. Be2 {8.Bd3 is quite
playable as well, but there is nothing wrong with delaying this confrontation.
White reasons that after 0-0 he will have a Rook on the f-file and Black's
Bishop will have to be watched carefully against discoveries.} 8... Be7 9. O-O
O-O 10. Rb1 $1 {A beautiful little intermezzo. White's weaknesses are
structural -- the pawns at a2 and c3, in particular, are vulnerable to attack
by ...Qa5. By provoking ...b6, White keeps the Black Queen from generating
counterplay. In a few more moves Black will be searching frantically for
counterplay, but to no avail!} 10... b6 {Black could, of course, defend b7
with a piece. But then the piece would be tied down to constant guard duty.}
11. Be3 {Playing to connect Rooks. White does not try anything fancy until his
mobilization is complete.} 11... Nc6 12. Qd2 (12. Qe1 $2 {
would drop the pawn at c2.}) (12. Nh4 $5 {is interesting:} 12... Bxh4 13. Rxf5
$16 {
leaves White with the Bishop pair and good attacking prospects on the kingside.
}) 12... Bg6 13. Ng5 $6 {An intriguing idea, but a bit hasty under the present
circumstances. Both sides overlook a tactic here.} 13... h6 $2 (13... cxd4 $1
14. cxd4 Nxd4 $1 {wins a pawn thanks to the overload on the Bishop at e3.}) 14.
Nh3 {Now the Black Kingside pawns have been weakened. White puts the Knight on
h3 not because it stands well there, but because it leaves the f-file open and
permits a later Nf4 if circumstances call for it. But chiefly White is
preparing a Bishop sacrifice on h6.} 14... c4 {This move releases what little
tension Black had in the center. It is essentially irrelevant to what follows
on the Kingside.} 15. Rf2 (15. Nf4 $5 {is a reasonable alternative here.})
15... Qd7 16. Rbf1 {Very instructive: White is building up in preparation for
the sacrifice rather than pulling the trigger prematurely. Now, with the
battery of Rooks on the f-file, he is ready to strike.} 16... Nd8 17. Bxh6 $5 {
I do not know whether this sacrifice is objectively sound in this position,
but it is a very good move from a practical standpoint. Black will have to
play perfectly from now on to avoid being crushed -- if, indeed, there is any
defense.} 17... gxh6 18. Qxh6 {Always the proper follow-up.} 18... Ne6 19. Rf6
$1 (19. Bg4 $1 {is another way to bring everything into the attack. The Black
pawn on f7 has several chores defending e6 and g6, so this move ties down
Black's Queen.} 19... Rfe8 {allows a beautiful mate by} 20. Rxf7 $3 Bxf7 21.
Rxf7 Kxf7 22. Qh7+ Kf8 23. Qh8+ Kf7 24. Bh5# {Frame it and hang it on the wall!
}) 19... Rfe8 {Now it's all over with a few sharp blows:} (19... Bxf6 20. exf6
Rae8 21. Ng5 $1 Bxc2 22. Rf3 {
and White swings the Rook over for mate on the h-file.}) 20. Rxg6+ fxg6 21.
Qxg6+ (21. Qxg6+ Ng7 22. Rf7 $1 {ends the conversation.}) 1-0

