1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 Nxc3 $2 {
The original Rube: Black fails to make White work to evict the Knight.} 6. bxc3
Be7 7. d4 {The fact that White gets this pawn to d4 in one move, instead of
taking two moves by stopping first on d3 to kick the Knight, is the measure of
the carelessness of Black's exchange on c3.} 7... O-O {It does not take a
genius to see that White will have serious attacking chances on the Kingside
thanks to his massive spatial edge there. The pawns point the way. In fact,
White must attack: if he wastes time, Black will get in ...f6 under favorable
circumstances and most of White's advantage will evaporate.} 8. Bd3 {This game 
is a great advertisement for White's opening setup. Extra space and long, open
diagonals for the Bishops, an open f-file, and the permanent address of the
enemy King -- what more can one want out of the opening?} 8... Bg4 9. Rb1 {
White often tosses in this move in the Vienna since it makes the Rook somewhat
more active and forces Black to make an awkward move on the Queenside.
Something gained and nothing lost -- whynot?} 9... b6 10. O-O {A multi-purpose
move for White in the Vienna. The pressure down the f-file is nice, but the
move also clears the e1 square for White's Queen to come to g3. It doesn't
happen in this game, but it is a very common maneuver.} 10... c5 {Black does
t really want to take White's d-pawn, since this would undouble White's pawns
for no particular reason. Instead, he wants to push forward with ...c4,
driving White's Bishop off of its dangerous diagonal leading to h7.} 11. h3 {
This is a subtle move with a brilliant idea behind it. White is pushing
Black's Bishop back to h5, not just because it is undefended there -- it is,
after all, undefended right where it sits -- but because White will be able to
capture it with check after the upcoming sacrifice.} 11... Bh5 {In hindsight,
Black would have done better to put this Bishop on a square like e6. The
problem here is that Black's Bishop is undefended on h5, and that gives White
license to pull off a brilliant coup.} 12. Bxh7+ $3 {A wonderful concept, the
full point of which does not become apparent until White's 16th move. Usually
this kind of sacrifice cannot be played when Black is in a position to take
the Knight as it arrives on g5. But here, White gets one piece back (the
Bishop on h5), and he has seen deeply enough to know what will happen after
that as well.} 12... Kxh7 13. Ng5+ Bxg5 {We should be grateful to Black for
finding this, the best defense, which forces White to play some beautiful
chess. Other moves are easier to break down since they lead to rapid mate or
catastrophic material loss.} (13... Kg6 {allows a neat mate with} 14. Qd3+ f5
15. exf6+ Kh6 16. Nf7# (16. Qh7# {also does the job.})) (13... Kh6 {
is likewise briskly mated by} 14. Nxf7+ Kh7 (14... Kg6 15. Qd3#) 15. Qxh5+ Kg8
16. Qh8#) (13... Kh8 {is arguably the worst of Black's options:} 14. Qxh5+ Kg8
15. Qh7#) 14. Qxh5+ Bh6 {Apparently Black has escaped with an extra piece.} 15.
Bxh6 $1 gxh6 (15... g6 {
is relatively best here, heading for an endgame a pawn down after} 16. Qg5 Qxg5
17. Bxg5 {when White has outstanding winning chances. Note the potential
mating net with Bf6 and Rf4-h4-h8.}) 16. Rf6 $1 {Now matters can be seen in
their true light. Black cannot bring anything else to the aid of the beseiged
h6 square.} 16... Kg7 17. Qxh6+ {All with checks, now!} 17... Kg8 18. Qg5+ $1
Kh7 19. Rh6# 1-0

[Event "EU-chT"]
[Site "Haifa"]
