{White's play in the opening is not particularly inspiring, but he makes up
for it with a resounding tactical finish.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5
Nxe4 5. Nf3 Be7 6. d3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 O-O 8. d4 (8. Be2 {might be even better
here, with the idea of getting castled quickly and then following up with d4.})
8... f6 9. Bd3 (9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Be2 {
is also possible, simply preparing to castle.}) 9... fxe5 10. Nxe5 Qe8 {
The one embarrassment in White's position is that he finds it difficult to
castle. The most natural way to take care of this problem would be to retreat
his Knight, but Black has thoughtfully discouraged this by setting up a
discovered check with ...Qe8.} 11. Qe2 {
White blocks the e-file so that he can retreat his Knight in peace.} (11. Nf3
$2 Bh4+ $17 {forces White to move his King to one side or the other, which is
embarrassing and awkward.}) 11... Nd7 12. Nf3 {Now White gratefully untangles.}
12... Bd6 13. O-O Nf6 (13... Qxe2 14. Bxe2 {is approximately equal, with
White's better-placed knight balancing his slightly weaker pawns.}) 14. Ne5 Nd7
{Wasn't this Knight on d7 just a move ago? Black is losing the time race.} (
14... c5 {is a better idea, immediately undermining the Knight and threatening
...c4 to trap White's Bishop.}) 15. Rxf8+ Nxf8 16. Bf4 {
White continues to develop at high speed, and he defends his Knight as well.} (
16. c4 $5 {is also interesting. White could play to open central lines for his
more active piece.}) 16... Ne6 17. Bg3 c5 18. Rf1 {With the arrival of White's
Rook on the f-file, the game has turned in White's favor.} 18... a6 $2 {
This move is irrelevant to the main action.} (18... c4 {would now be crushed by
} 19. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 20. Nf7 $3 $18 {
and Black has to start handing over heavy material to stop mate in two.}) 19.
Nf7 $1 {Decisive! White hits d6 while simultaneously setting up tactics on the
kingside.} 19... Qf8 {Black apparently resigned here without waiting for White
to play the mate in three.} (19... Bxg3 20. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Qh8#
) (19... Qf8 20. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Qh8#) 1-0

