1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3 {
It is simplest to stop checks like this.} 5... Be7 6. d3 {White intends to put
this pawn on d4, but he pauses to kick Black's Knight out first. This loses a
tempo, but it makes White's space advantage more stable.} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 O-O
8. d4 {The pawn chain is in place now, and White needs only 9.Be3 and 10.0-0
to complete a very comfortable setup.} 8... Bf5 9. Bd3 {White does not worry
about exchanging Bishops here, since this gives him an extra center pawn.} 9...
Bxd3 10. cxd3 c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. d4 $1 {And now the strong central pawn
chain is put back in place, all with a gain of time.} 12... Bb6 $2 {Undoubtedly
...Be7 was better here. The Bishop is wholly out of play on b6, and Black
needs some help in organizing the move ...f6.} 13. O-O Nc6 14. Qd3 {Now White t
hreatens to weaken the Black Kingside pawns with 15.Ng5 g6 16.Qh3 h5.} 14... h6
15. Qf5 Qc8 16. Qh5 {White has no desire to trade Queens. His space advantage
on the Kingside indicates that he should attack there, and an attack on the
enemy King is nearly always more powerful when Queens are still on the board.}
16... Qe6 17. Kh1 {White would like to play 17.Nh4 preparing moves like Nf5 or
even the sacrifice Rf6. But his Knight is needed to help defend e5 right now
because his d-pawn is pinned. So he unpins the pawn, giving his pieces more
freedom.} 17... Bd8 18. Rb1 Na5 19. Rb2 Rc8 20. Rc2 Qa6 21. Kg1 Nc4 22. Rcf2 {
Now the Rooks are doubled on the open f-file and tactical possibilities are in
the air.} 22... Qg6 23. Qh3 {Once again White declines to trade Queens.} 23...
Ba5 {Hitting the weak pawn on c3 -- but this is far from the field of battle.}
24. Nh4 $1 {A great multi-purpose move. White opens the f-file, defends his
pawn laterally with his Queen, and hits Black's Queen.} 24... Qe6 25. Nf5 (25.
Qg3 $1 {is also very strong, threatening 26.Rf6. Then} 25... Kh8 {
leaves Black's Rook on f8 inadequately defended, so:} 26. Ng6+ $1 fxg6 27.
Rxf8+ {picks up the exchange, and after} 27... Rxf8 28. Rxf8+ Kh7 29. Qf3 {
White dominates the only fully open file. He now threatens 30.Rb8 and Qf8 with
mate threats, or (more dramatically) 30.Bxh6!! and Black falls apart. For
example:} 29... b5 30. Rb8 $1 {This is even simpler.} (30. Bxh6 gxh6 (30...
Kxh6 {allows the amusing finish} 31. Rh8+ Kg5 32. h4#) 31. Rf7+ Kh8 (31... Kg8
32. Rxa7 {threatening Ra8+ and Qf8 with mating threats from behind the King.})
32. Rf6 {and the g-pawn falls because} 32... Qe8 {runs into} 33. Rf8+ $18)
30... Bb6 31. Qf8 g5 32. Qh8+ Kg6 33. Rb7 {
and Black has no good way to defend g7.}) 25... Rc6 {
Walking into something nice.} 26. Bxh6 $1 (26. Bxh6 gxh6 27. Qg4+ Qg6 28. Ne7+
{picks up the Queen.}) 1-0

