1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O 8.
Be2 $1 {White holds back on d4, playing to get castled quickly and comfortably
before beginning any skirmishes.} 8... f6 9. O-O fxe5 10. Nxe5 Bf6 11. Bf4 (11.
d4 $5 {is worth a look if White feels a strong urge to sharpen the position.
White's pawns will not be pretty, but he will have more space and the Bishop
pair.}) (11. Ba3 $5 {is very interesting. After the more or less forced reply}
11... Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Rxf8+ Qxf8 14. d4 {White has just a slight
advantage in space, but Black can probably hold the balance with} 14... Nd7 $11
) 11... Nd7 12. d4 Nxe5 13. dxe5 {White accepts broken pawns on the queenside
in return for the space that the e-pawn gives him and the consequent attacking
chances. In any event, he could not have avoided broken pawns by capturing
with a piece on e5 as Black would simply have swapped there again.} 13... Be7
14. Bd3 {
Now White has ideas like Qh5 in view, taking advantage of the weakness of h7.}
14... g6 {Black is understandably worried about the weakness of his h7 square,
but this pawn now becomes a potential target.} 15. Qd2 {White connects his
Rooks before playing Bh6 so that if Black captures on f1, White can recapture
with his other Rook.} 15... Be6 16. Bh6 Rf7 (16... Rxf1+ 17. Rxf1) 17. Rxf7
Bxf7 18. Rf1 Qd7 19. Qf4 Bc5+ 20. Kh1 Bf8 21. h4 Bxh6 22. Qxh6 {Now White's
Queen is one of the things pressing on g6, and Black must exercise caution.}
22... Qe7 23. Re1 Be6 {Momentary inattention. Likely Black had calculated some
of what now happens but had not seen all the way to the end.} (23... Qe6 24. h5
$13 {is still interesting and double-edged.}) 24. Bxg6 $1 {
This sacrifice is finely calculated.} 24... hxg6 25. Qxg6+ Kh8 26. Qh6+ $1 Qh7
{Black counts on the fork at a4 to regain his material. But he has overlooked
a Zwischenzug.} (26... Kg8 27. Re3 $1 $18) 27. Qf6+ $1 Qg7 {
Reluctantly Black abandons the surveillance of the h4 pawn.} ({Or} 27... Kg8 {
when} 28. Qxe6+ {comes with check.}) 28. Qxe6 Rg8 29. Qf6 {Simplest.} 29... Rf8
30. Qxg7+ Kxg7 {White will ram the e-pawn forward, leaving Black no choice but
to blockade it with his Rook. Then White will bring his own King and kingside
pawns forward, giving up his Rook and his e-pawn for Black's Rook at the first
available moment and winning easily.} 1-0

[Event "US op"]
[Site "Chicago"]
[Date "1989.08.??"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Larsen, James"]
[Black "Levine, David M"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C29"]
[Annotator "McGrew 2007"]
[PlyCount "65"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3 {Once again we see how the
Oxford Variation can transpose back into our main lines.} 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Be7
7. Be2 O-O 8. Nf3 f6 9. exf6 (9. O-O {is also good here.}) 9... Bxf6 10. d4 Nc6
11. O-O Re8 12. Bd3 Be6 13. Ng5 $3 {
Inspired play! The point becomes apparent only several moves later.} 13... Bxg5
(13... h6 14. Nxe6 Rxe6 15. Qg4 Qe8 16. Rb1 (16. Bxh6 Bxd4+ $1 17. cxd4 Rxh6
$16 {minimizes White's advantage.}) 16... b6 17. Qf5 $1 $18) 14. Qh5 $1 Bh6 {
apparently covering everything.} 15. Bxh6 gxh6 16. Qxh6 Qd7 (16... Re7 17. Rf3
$1 $18 {gives White a strong enough attack that Black will have to lose
material beating it off.}) 17. Rf6 Kh8 18. Raf1 $1 {Now White threatens 19.
Rf7!! and Black is suddenly confronted with overwhelming threats.} 18... Re7
19. Bf5 $3 {Wonderful tactical alertness!} 19... Bg8 (19... Bxf5 20. Rf8+ Rxf8
21. Qxf8#) 20. Bxd7 {The rest of the game is an anticlimax.} 20... Rxd7 21. Rf8
Rxf8 22. Rxf8 Rd6 23. Rf6 Rd7 24. g4 Rg7 25. g5 Ne7 26. h4 Nc8 27. Rf8 Nd6 28.
h5 Ne4 29. g6 Nxc3 30. Rxg8+ Kxg8 31. Qg5 hxg6 32. h6 Rd7 33. Qxg6+ 1-0

