1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3 {The Oxford Variation.} 5...
Nxc3 {Capturing on c3 is by far the most common move.} (5... Bb4 {
This is an old drawing line. White can avoid the draw, but only at some risk.}
6. dxe4 {Black has two big ideas here: taking the Knight on c3 (to weaken e4)
and checking with his Queen on h4. It turns out that it matters very much what
order these moves come in. An inexact move order will leave Black a piece down
for nothing.} 6... Qh4+ $1 {This is the right move order, reserving the
possibility of ...Bc5+ should White play g3.} (6... Bxc3+ $2 {It is important
for Black to take the Knight either now or next move, in any event before
White can unpin and move it. But this looks like it's one move too early.} 7.
bxc3 Qh4+ 8. g3 {This move looks insane, but computer-assisted analysis (begun
on my birthday in May 2006) has convinced me that White may be able to trap
Black's Queen. If this works, it refutes the combination of Black's piece
sacrifice with the immediate exchange of the Bishop on c3.} (8. Ke2 Bg4+ {
This is the main line.} 9. Nf3 dxe4 10. Qd4 $1 Bh5 $1 11. Ke3 $1 Bxf3 {
If White does not want to draw, there is one last chance here to opt out.} 12.
gxf3 (12. Bb5+ c6 13. gxf3 cxb5 14. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 15. Kxe4 Nd7 {According to
theory, White's centralized King and his Bishop give him slightly the better
of this ending, though with good play Black should draw.}) 12... Qe1+ 13. Kf4
Qh4+ 14. Ke3 Qe1+ $11) 8... Qxe4+ 9. Kf2 Qxh1 10. Nf3 {
The box snaps shut. Now the threat is Bb5+ winning Black's Queen.} 10... O-O (
10... Nc6 {This position is critical. What is White's best move?} 11. Qxd5 $1
Be6 (11... Bg4 12. Bg2 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxh2 14. Bf4 Nxe5 15. Re1 $1 {White keeps
the Bishop trained on the h6 square, preventing the escape of the Black Queen.}
) 12. Qb5 $1 {Now White threatens both Qxb7 and Bb2 followed by Bg2.} 12...
O-O-O 13. Rb1 Rd5 (13... b6 14. Bf4) 14. Qxb7+ Kd7 15. Bb5 Rxb5 16. Qxb5 Rb8
17. Qd3+ Kc8 18. Rxb8+ Nxb8 19. Be3 $14) (10... c6 11. Qd4 $1 $18 {The Queen ke
eps an eye on d1 (so Black's Queen can't escape there) and g4 (to prevent ...
Bg4).}) 11. Qd2 Bg4 12. Bg2 Bxf3 13. Bxh1 Bxh1 14. Ba3 $18 {Black loses the
exchange, leaving White with a Queen for two minor pieces -- a technical win,
though not without interest.}) 7. Ke2 (7. g3 $4 Qxe4+ $1 {By refraining from
capturing on c3, Black gives himself the option of harrassing the King with ...
Bc5+.} 8. Kf2 $4 Bc5+ {mates}) 7... Bg4+ ({Harding and Barden comment that} 
7... Nc6 {"is also strong," but this looks highly dubious, e.g.} 8. Nf3 Bg4 9.
Nxd5 O-O-O 10. Bf4 $18 {
and Black frankly doesn't look like having nearly enough for the piece.}) 8.
Nf3 Bxc3 {
Now this is right, since Black wants to take the pawn on e4 to exploit the pin.
} 9. bxc3 dxe4 10. Qd4 $1 {
A hard move to find. White is setting up a pin across the fourth rank.} 10...
Bh5 $1 {Black backs the Bishop out of the pin.} (10... exf3+ 11. gxf3 Bxf3+ 12.
Kxf3 $18) (10... Bxf3+ 11. gxf3 $18) 11. Ke3 {White unpins in turn. Quite
complex stuff! Now Black must find an "only move" to stay in the game.} 11...
Bxf3 {This is the only serious branch point, as White has to decide whether to
pocket half a point or play for a win.} 12. Bb5+ {This is the winning attempt.}
(12. gxf3 {This is the right move if White is content with a draw.} 12... Qe1+
(12... Nc6 $2 13. Bb5 $18) 13. Kf4 Qh4+ $11 (13... Nc6 $4 14. Qd7+ $1 Kxd7 15.
Bh3+ Ke8 16. Rxe1 $18)) 12... c6 13. gxf3 cxb5 14. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 15. Kxe4 Nd7 {
Theory gives White a slight edge in this position, though Black should be able
to hold. But it is a difficult position, and anyone going into this line
should examine some classic games before trying to play it.}) (5... Qh4+ $2 {
With this move, Black falls into Wuerzburger's Trap.} 6. g3 Nxg3 7. Nf3 Qh5 8.
Nxd5 $1 {Now Black cannot defend the pawn at c7 or he loses his Knight in a
very entertaining way.} 8... Na6 9. Nf4 Qh6 10. Ne2 Qc6 11. Nxg3 $18) 6. bxc3 {
This is the real crossroads of the Oxford, since Black must choose where he
wants to place his pawns and pieces.} 6... Nc6 {This move and 6...d4 are apt
to transpose into one another, but this does give White one chance to go wrong.
} (6... d4 7. Nf3 Nc6 (7... dxc3 8. d4 (8. Be3 Nc6 9. Be2 Qd5 10. O-O Nxe5 11.
Qe1 Ng4) 8... Be6 (8... Qd5) 9. Bb5+ c6 10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Qe1) 8.
cxd4) (6... c5 {The purpose of this move is to prevent White from carrying out
the "big center" plan in our main line.}) (6... Be7 {This somewhat unusual
move is perhaps Black's best if he does not intend to continue with a quick ...
d4. Black will castle and then decide how to continue. If White has played d4,
Black will counter with ...c5; he may also play ...f6 to eliminate White's
space advantage. If White does not play d4 but instead chooses the more
compact plan of development with Nf3, Be2, and 0-0, Black will probably
content himself with ...f6.}) 7. Nf3 d4 8. cxd4 $5 Nxd4 (8... Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+
10. Qxd2 Nxd4 11. c3 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 Qh4+ (12... O-O 13. O-O-O Qd5 14. d4) (
12... f6 13. f4 (13. O-O-O fxe5 14. f4)) 13. Qf2 Qf4 (13... Qe7 14. d4 f6 15.
O-O-O fxe5 16. Re1 O-O) 14. Qg3 Qe3+ (14... Qh6) 15. Be2 O-O (15... Bf5 16. f4
Qc5 17. d4) 16. f4) 9. c3 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 {Black is already somewhat worse, and
a careless pawn move at this point could allow White to whip up a devastating
attack.} 10... c6 {Probably best. Black plans ...Be6 to keep White from
building pressure against f7.} (10... f6 11. d4 $1 fxe5 (11... c6 12. Bc4 {
leaves Black paralyzed.}) 12. Bb5+ $1 c6 13. O-O $1 Qf6 (13... Be6 {Trying to b
lock the diagonal before White can play Bc4. But now there are too many
vulnerable points in the Black position and he collapses tactically.} 14. Bxc6+
bxc6 15. Qxc6+ Bd7 16. Qd5 $1 {A lovely abstract fork.} 16... Qc8 (16... Bf5
17. Qxe5+ Be7 18. Qxf5 Rf8 19. Qh5+ g6 20. Rxf8+ Bxf8 21. Qxh7 $18 {
Three extra pawns and a safe King -- works for me!}) 17. Qf7+ Kd8 18. Bg5+ Kc7
19. Qc4+ Bc6 20. Rf7+ Kb6 21. Bd8+ Qxd8 22. Rb1+ Ka5 23. Qxc6 a6 24. Rb4 Bxb4
25. cxb4+ Kxb4 26. Rb7+ {and White mates.}) 14. Qg3 $18) (10... c5 11. d4 cxd4
12. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 13. e6 fxe6 14. O-O $18) 11. d4 Be6 12. Bd3 Bd5 13. Qf2 Be7 14.
O-O O-O 15. Bh6 $1 f6 (15... gxh6 16. Qf5 Re8 17. Qxh7+ Kf8 18. Qh8#) 16. Qf5
g6 17. Qg4 Rf7 18. e6 Rg7 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. c4 {
1-0 Groeber,E-Bochler/Germany 1988} (20. c4 f5 21. Qe2 $18) *

