1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 {
It is fascinating how often Black chooses this move, which is clearly not best.
} 6. bxc3 c6 $2 {This passive move takes away a good square from Black's
Knight and wastes a tempo if Black ever intended to play ...c5 later to
challenge White's center.} 7. d4 Be7 8. Bd3 Nd7 9. Ne2 {In the bxc3 lines,
White often brings this Knight out at e2 and then later decides whether to
play with Nf4 or Ng3-f5 (or -h5).} 9... Nf8 $2 {Black reasons that because the
center is somewhat blocked, he can get away with a slow redeployment of his
forces. But this is an illusion.} 10. O-O {
With the threat of a fatal capture on f7.} 10... Be6 (10... f6 11. exf6 Bxf6
12. Ba3 $1 {gives Black horrible headaches.} 12... Kf7 13. Nf4 $18) 11. Nf4 $1
{The Knight very often comes out here in this variation. White's advantage is
already nearly decisive.} 11... Qd7 12. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 ({
Black realizes a little too late that} 12... Qxe6 13. Bf5 $18 {wins the Queen.}
) 13. Qf7+ Kd8 14. Qxg7 {White wins the Rook. It all looked so simple!} 1-0

