1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 {Jana Krivec has made this
move her personal specialty -- and it has paid off handsomely for her in a
nice string of tournament games.} 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 {Against the immediate
Knight capture on c3, Krivec consistently recaptures with the d-pawn.} 6...
Qh4+ {Black decides to make it an endgame immediately -- not a wise choice,
since the pawn on e4 turns out to be rather weak.} 7. g3 Qe4+ 8. Qxe4 dxe4 9.
Bg2 $1 {Fritz says that the position is about equal, but Black is actually
already in difficulties.} 9... Nc6 10. Bf4 Bf5 11. O-O-O Bc5 (11... h6 12. h4
Bc5 13. Re1 Bf2 14. Re2 e3 15. Bf3 $1 {Preventing ...Bg4.} 15... O-O-O 16. Nh3
$14 {Black's pieces do not coordinate as well as they might appear to. The
Bishop on f2 is buried out of play -- the price Black had to pay to hold onto
the e-pawn.}) 12. Re1 $1 {There goes the pawn! White has to realize that in a
position like this, it is more important to pick off the e-pawn than it is to
maintain control of the d-file. Later, White can if necessary challenge Black
for control of that file again.} 12... h6 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Rxe4 g5 15. Bd2 (
15. Be3 $1 Bxe3+ 16. Rxe3 O-O-O 17. Nf3 {gives White a plus, not only because
of the extra pawn but also because Black's pawn at f7 is backward and could
become vulnerable.}) 15... O-O-O 16. Nf3 Rhe8 17. Rhe1 Re6 18. b4 Bf8 19. Nd4
Rg6 20. Rf1 (20. a3) 20... Re8 $2 (20... Bxb4 21. cxb4 Rxd4 22. Rxd4 Nxd4 23.
Rxf7 $16) 21. Rxf7 (21. Nxc6 $1 Rxc6 22. Rxf7) 21... Nd8 22. Rf2 Bg7 23. Rf5
Re7 24. Rf1 (24. Be3 Nf7 25. Rf1 Rxe5 26. Rxe5 Nxe5 27. Nf5 Bf8 28. Bd4 $16 {
White is better, but this endgame could prove difficult to win because White's
queenside majority cannot produce a passed pawn by force.}) 24... Rxe5 25. Rfe1
Rxe4 26. Rxe4 Kd7 27. Nf5 Ne6 28. g4 Bf8 29. c4 Bd6 30. h4 $1 Bf4 31. h5 $1
Bxd2+ 32. Kxd2 Rf6 33. c5 a6 34. c4 Kd8 35. Re5 c6 36. Ke3 Kd7 37. a3 Rf8 $2 {
Black mistakenly believes that White must allow a damaging Rook penetration if
she takes the h-pawn. This may have been a time pressure blunder.} 38. Nxh6 Rf4
39. Re4 $1 Rf1 40. Ke2 $1 Ra1 41. Re3 $1 Nf4+ 42. Kf2 Ra2+ 43. Kf3 Ra1 44. Nf5
Rf1+ 45. Ke4 Rg1 46. h6 Rh1 47. Ke5 Ke8 48. Kf6+ {Black is now obviously lost.}
48... Kf8 49. Re7 {Just one of many ways to win.} (49. Kxg5 {
is also completely winning.}) (49. Nd6 {
wins a piece because of the mate threat:} 49... Rxh6+ 50. Kxg5 Rh7 51. Kxf4)
49... Kg8 50. Kxg5 (50. h7+ Rxh7 $2 (50... Kh8 51. Nd6 $18) 51. Re8#) 50...
Nh3+ 51. Kf6 Rg1 52. Rg7+ ({Or} 52. h7+ Kh8 53. Nh4 $1 Nf4 54. g5 $18 {
etc. There is no danger of a stalemate with Black's queenside pawns still on
the board.}) 52... Kh8 53. Nd6 Rf1+ 54. Ke7 {
Black runs out of checks and then has to give up a piece to prevent Nf7#} 1-0

[Event "Athens Acropolis (Women) op"]
[Site "Athens"]
[Date "2003.08.25"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Krivec, Jana"]
[Black "Karlovich, Anastazia"]
