[Annotator "McGrew 2009"]
[PlyCount "119"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 {
Krivec's consistent choice.} 6... Qh4+ {
Black opts to play the endgame immediately.} 7. g3 Qe4+ 8. Qxe4 dxe4 9. Bg2 Bf5
(9... Nc6 10. Bf4) 10. Ne2 $1 {Since Black has not attacked e5 immediately,
White is free to direct the Knight toward the d4 square where it will assail
Black's undefended Bishop.} 10... Nc6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 {This is a very
bad result for Black. White has straightened out her queenside pawns,
reinforced e5, and retained good central control.} 12... Rd8 13. c3 c5 14. Be3
({White could insert} 14. Rf1 {here first.}) 14... cxd4 15. Bxd4 $1 {Much bette
r than capturing with the pawn. Now White's Bishop dominates the dark squares
and Black's pawn at e4 is doomed.} 15... Be7 16. O-O Bg6 17. Rae1 {
Preparing to pick off the pawn.} 17... O-O 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 {White's posi
tion is a technical win now -- slow, and requiring technique, but sheer misery
for the defender.} 19... Rd5 20. b4 Bg5 21. h4 Bh6 22. g4 g6 23. g5 Bg7 24. a4
Rc8 25. Kg2 a5 26. b5 Rc4 27. Ra1 {Don't give away pawns unnecessarily!} 27...
Kf8 28. Kf3 Ke7 29. Ke3 Ke6 30. Kd3 Rc8 31. c4 (31. Rf1) 31... Rd7 32. Rf1 Rc5
33. Kc3 Rc8 34. Kb3 Ra8 35. Rff4 (35. c5 {is strong now.}) 35... Rad8 36. c5
Rd5 37. Kc4 Rc8 38. b6 (38. Rxf7 $1 Rxd4+ 39. Rxd4 Kxf7 40. Rd7+ Kg8 41. e6 {
and the pawns overwhelm Black's defenses.}) 38... Rd7 39. Kb5 Bf8 40. Kc4 Be7
41. Re2 Rcd8 42. Rb2 h6 43. gxh6 g5 44. hxg5 Bxg5 45. Re4 Bxh6 46. Rf2 Bg5 47.
Rg4 Be7 48. Rh2 Kf5 49. Rhg2 Ke6 50. Rf4 Rd5 51. Rg7 f6 52. Rg6 $1 Kf7 53. Rh6
f5 54. Rxf5+ Kg7 55. Rd6 $1 Bxd6 56. exd6+ Rxd4+ 57. Kxd4 Rh8 58. Kd5 (58. c6
$1 bxc6 59. b7 Rb8 60. d7 $18) 58... Rh1 59. d7 Kg6 60. Ke4 (60. Rg5+ Kxg5 61.
d8=Q+ {and Black is in check, so there is no time for ...Rd1+.}) 1-0

