1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 $6 6. bxc3 {Gergely Antal
specializes in this move. White gives up the option of castling queenside but
maintains space and a very free development. However, White must be aware that
in one principal line this continuation leads to a more or less forced draw.}
6... Be7 7. d4 c5 (7... O-O 8. Bd3 f6 9. Qh5 {is a fast path to a draw:} 9...
g6 10. Bxg6 (10. Qh6 {
is possible but riskier -- why take chances you don't have to?}) 10... hxg6 11.
Qxg6+ Kh8 {Now White cannot afford to give Black any spare moves, otherwise ...
Qe8 will provide defensive resources. So the wisest course is to take a
perpetual.} 12. Qh6+ (12. Nh3 {is too risky:} 12... Qe8 $1 (12... Bxh3 $4 13.
Qh5+ Kg8 14. gxh3 Rf7 15. Rg1+ Rg7 16. Rxg7+ Kxg7 17. e6 $18) 13. Qh6+ Kg8 14.
e6 Bxe6 15. O-O Bxh3 16. Qxh3 Qd7 17. Qg3+ Kf7 $17) 12... Kg8 13. Qg6+ Kh8 14.
Qh6+ Kg8 15. Qg6+ $11) 8. Bd3 {White's moves are all extremely natural.} 8...
O-O 9. Ne2 {The Knight typically comes out at e2 here and then heads for f4.}
9... Be6 (9... c4 10. Bf5 $14) 10. O-O Nc6 (10... c4 {does not win a piece
here because, by contrast with the French Defense, Black has a Bishop on e6
rather than a pawn. White can simply play} 11. Bf5 $14 {with the idea of
capturing on e6 and later giving Black's pawn a hard time there.}) 11. Be3 Rc8
12. Nf4 Bg5 $2 13. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 (13... Bxe3+ 14. Qxe3 fxe6 15. Qh3 $1 $18) 14.
Qxf8+ $1 (14. Qxf8+ Qxf8 15. Rxf8+ Rxf8 16. Bxg5 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nxd4 18. Rb1 b6
19. c4 $18) 1-0

