1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 {
Krivec's favorite line.} 6... Be7 7. Bf4 O-O 8. O-O-O {This move has two good
purposes: first, to give Black's pawn on d5 some grief, and second, to get
White's King out of the center in anticipation of an all-out kingside attack.}
8... c6 9. h4 $1 {This is a clever way for White (after castling queenside!)
to accelerate the kingside attack. Black dare not touch this pawn, and later
it will prove useful as a support for a N/g5.} 9... Qa5 {Not very subtle.} (
9... Bxh4 $4 {loses a piece at once to} 10. Qh5 $18) 10. Kb1 {
This is the simplest way to defend a2.} 10... Be6 11. Qg3 {
With the blunt threat of Bh6.} 11... Kh8 (11... Re8 {
is perhaps the best defense, but White should come out of it on top:} {
White could also probe the Black kingside with} 12. h5 (12. Nf3 Nd7 13. Bd3 Nc5
14. Nd4 Nxd3 15. cxd3 Bf8 16. h5 c5 17. Nxe6 Rxe6 18. h6 g6 19. Qf3 Rd8 20.
Rhf1 $14 {
and White is clearly more comfortable, with the idea of Bg5 in many lines.})
12... Bf8 13. Nf3 (13. h6 g6 14. Nf3 d4 15. c4 $1 c5 16. Ng5 $14) 13... Nd7 14.
Bd3 Nc5 15. Ng5 h6 16. Nxe6 Rxe6 17. Bf5 $16) 12. Nf3 Nd7 13. Ng5 Qa4 (13... h6
14. Qd3 $1 Bxg5 15. hxg5 d4 16. a3 dxc3 17. gxh6 g6 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 $16
{White has an extra pawn and the Bishop pair.}) 14. Bd3 d4 {This is pretty
much Black's only direct tactical trick. Be aware of it and don't lose your
shirt on a2!} 15. b3 $1 {Gaining a tempo.} 15... Qa5 16. cxd4 {Now White has
an extra pawn, a huge central presence, and ... oh yes, a threat against h7.}
16... c5 (16... h6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Qg6 Kg8 19. Qh7+ Kf7 20. Bg6#) 17. Nxh7 (
17. Qf3 $1 {is even stronger, repositioning the Queen to come in at h5 but
also threatening d5 winning a piece.} 17... c4 (17... g6 18. d5 $18) 18. Bxh7
cxb3 19. cxb3 Rfe8 20. Qh5 $18) 17... cxd4 18. Nxf8 Rxf8 19. Qf3 {
Now White mops up -- it's not quick, but it's also not in doubt.} 19... f5 20.
exf6 Rxf6 21. Qe4 Kg8 22. Bg5 Nc5 23. Qh7+ Kf8 24. Qh8+ Kf7 25. Qh5+ (25. Bxf6
{is simple and good.}) 25... Kf8 26. Bxf6 Bxf6 27. Rhe1 Qa3 28. Rxe6 (28. Bb5
$1 Bf7 29. Re8+ Bxe8 30. Qxe8#) 28... Nxe6 29. Re1 Qd6 30. Bc4 d3 31. Rxe6
dxc2+ 32. Kxc2 {There are no checks.} 1-0

