1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be6 $6 {
This move does nothing to put pressure on White's center and sets no traps.} (
6... Be7 {at least prevents Qg3 before White has castled. Of course, White
does just that:} 7. Bf4 ({Not} 7. Qg3 $4 Bh4 $19) 7... O-O 8. O-O-O c6 9. h4 {
with good attacking chances.}) 7. Qg3 {This move frees the f3 square for a
Knight and makes it awkward for Black to develop the kingside.} 7... Nc6 8. Nf3
h6 9. Bb5 (9. Bd3 {is also fine.}) 9... a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Be3 g6 12. O-O {
Black has created a weakness at f6, so White castles kingside -- avoiding the
open b-file, which could have assisted Black in mounting an attack had White's
King gone the other direction.} 12... Be7 13. Nd4 {
Very nice centralization. All of White's pieces now find good squares.} 13...
Qd7 {There is no other move that hangs onto all of the material.} 14. Rf2 {
White prepares to double on the f-file.} (14. Qf2 {also makes sense. White
prevents ...c5 and prepares to clamp down on that square.}) 14... c5 15. Nb3 c4
{Here Black overextends. If White's Knight had to go to d4, Black might be
able to make something of a later ...c5. But in the present position, White
has a more active option.} (15... Qc6) 16. Nc5 $1 Bxc5 17. Bxc5 {Now Black cann
ot castle kingside and cannot oppose White's Bishop. This is one of those
positions where the presence of Bishops of opposite colors actually hurts the
defender.} 17... Qb5 18. Ba3 {Of course: White defends the b-pawn and keeps
Black's King trapped in the center.} 18... O-O-O {This is a risky decision
because of the dilapidated state of the queenside, but it is hard to suggest
something better.} 19. b3 {The main purpose of this move is simply to defend
the b-pawn, freeing the Bishop to do what it does next.} 19... d4 20. Be7 $1 {
The Bishop has done all it can on its present diagonal; Black's King has fled
to the side of the board where it is most likely that lines will open up.
White therefore seizes the moment to transfer the Bishop to the dream square
f6, where it will take away the d8 square from Black's Rooks.} 20... Rd7 21.
Bf6 {Now Black's position is supremely discoordinated.} 21... Re8 22. cxd4 Rxd4
23. Qe3 {There goes a pawn if White wants it.} 23... Qd7 24. Raf1 (24. b4 {
with ideas like a4 and opening queenside lines is also very strong.}) 24... h5
25. Rf4 Rxf4 26. Qxf4 Qd5 27. h4 (27. Qe3 {also looks good, again intending
some kind of queenside infiltration. With Queens on, this is not drawish.})
27... c5 28. Kh2 Kc7 29. Qc1 {This is a nice idea. Black has no chance of
whipping up an attack on the kingside, so White transfers the Queen to a3 in
order to probe at the weak queenside pawns, particularly the pawn on a6.} 29...
Bg4 30. Qa3 cxb3 31. axb3 Kb6 32. Ra1 {So Black cannot prevent White's Queen
from checking at a5. Things now go sour for Black in a hurry.} 32... Ra8 (32...
Bc8 {was the lesser evil.}) 33. Qa5+ Kc6 34. Ra4 $1 {The threat is to put the
Rook on c4 and then explore ways of tormenting the pawn at c5.} 34... Be2 {
Black stops Rc4.} 35. c4 $6 {A small slip. This move is positionally desirable,
but it would be better for White's Rook to be on the other side of the c-pawn
to prevent Black's Queen from staying centralized.} (35. Rf4 $1 Bg4 36. c4 $18
{When the Queen moves, White will completely break up Black's pawns with 37.b4.
}) 35... Qd4 36. Ra1 Qf4+ 37. Kh1 Qe3 38. Re1 $1 {Now White is back on track.}
38... Qd3 39. Be7 Qd4 40. Rxe2 (40. Rxe2 Qd1+ 41. Re1 $18) 1-0

