1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Nc6 {The hit on
5 can be met in one of two ways. Krivec chooses to get rid of the Knight.} 7.
Bb5 (7. Bf4 {is also reasonable.}) 7... Be7 8. Bf4 {There is no reason to take
on c6 until Black provokes it with ...a6 or breaks the pin with ...Bd7
(threatening a boomerang on e5).} 8... Be6 (8... Bd7 {would allow} 9. Qxd5) 9.
O-O-O a6 {There's the signal to take on c6.} 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qg3 Bf8 (11...
O-O 12. Bh6 $18) 12. Nf3 Qd7 13. c4 $1 {When you have a Rook on the half-open
d-file, you can play in the center as well as on the wings!} 13... g6 14. Ng5
$5 {This is a very clever idea.} (14. Bg5 $1 {might well be even stronger, e.g.
} 14... Bg7 15. Qh4 h6 16. Bf6 g5 17. Qd4 Bxf6 18. exf6 $16) 14... Bg7 {
Black misses the point.} (14... Bf5 15. Rhe1 Bg7 16. Ne4 Bxe4 17. Rxe4 Qe6 18.
Red4 $14) 15. Ne4 $1 {Oh dear! That Knight is going to cause a LOT of trouble!}
15... Rb8 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. exf6 {Here again, with Queens on the board, the
opposite color Bishops do not really save Black any trouble: instead, they
fuel the attack.} 17... Rb7 18. Qa3 $1 {
Preventing castling and striking at the undefended pawn at a6.} 18... Qd8 {
Black hopes to pick up the annoying pawn at f6.} 19. Be5 (19. Rhe1 {
is also playable since a6 is hanging, e.g.} 19... Qxf6 20. Be5 Qg5+ 21. Kb1 Rg8
22. Qxa6 $18) 19... a5 20. Rhe1 Rb4 21. cxd5 cxd5 22. Qxa5 {This is adequate,
but White misses a chance to make use of all of the tactical features of the
position here.} (22. c3 $1 Rb6 23. Rxd5 $1 Bxd5 24. Bxc7+ $18) 22... Rc4 23. b3
Rc6 24. Qb4 Rb6 25. Qc5 c6 26. Bd4 (26. c4 $1 {would create overwhelming
threats. Black is playing a Rook down -- the Rook on h8 is not really in the
game.}) 26... Ra6 27. Rxe6+ $1 fxe6 28. f7+ Kxf7 29. Rf1+ (29. Rf1+ Kg8 30.
Bxh8 Kxh8 31. Rf8+ {etc.}) 1-0

