1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 $6 {
This natural reaction seems to guarantee White at least a small advantage.} 6.
bxc3 {White goes for a big center.} 6... Be6 (6... Qh4+ 7. g3 Qe4+ 8. Qxe4 dxe4
9. Bg2 Bf5 10. Ne2 $14) (6... Be7 7. d4 c5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Ne2 Be6 10. O-O Nc6
11. Be3 Rc8 12. Nf4 Bg5 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qxf8+ {
1-0 Antal,G (2478)-Hart,D (2065)/Millfield 2004}) 7. Ne2 Nc6 8. d4 Ne7 9. Nf4
Bf5 10. Bd3 c6 11. O-O {White is already seriously better here.} 11... g6 12.
g4 (12. Nh5 $1 {gives White a huge plus. The threat of a check on f6 is more
than Black can bear, but letting his pawns be shattered won't help either:}
12... gxh5 13. Bxf5 Nxf5 14. Qxf5 Qd7 15. Qxh5 O-O-O 16. Bg5 Re8 17. Rxf7 $18)
12... Bxd3 $4 ({Black had to give up a pawn here with} 12... Be4 13. Bxe4 dxe4
14. Qxe4 $18 {although he is quite lost here.}) 13. Nxd3 {
Black resigns. There is no good way to defend f7.} 1-0

