1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 $6 6. bxc3 Be7 7. Ne2 (7.
d4 {is also quite simple and strong.}) 7... O-O 8. Nf4 c6 9. d4 Re8 10. Bd3 Bg5
11. O-O {If White is allowed to play these moves without being pushed in some
other way, Black almost always stands much worse. Here, he is more or less
lost already.} 11... h6 12. Nh3 $1 Be6 13. Nxg5 hxg5 14. Qh5 $1 {
Trouble incoming at h7!} 14... Qa5 (14... g6 15. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 16. Qxg6+ Kh8 17.
Bxg5 {and White mates shortly.}) (14... Nd7 15. Qh7+ Kf8 16. Ba3+ $1 {
Oh -- that way!} 16... c5 17. dxc5 Qa5 18. Bb4 $1 $18) 15. Bxg5 {Black resigns.
White's Bishop on g5 covers the Black King's escape route at e7, so a check on
h7 and another on h8 spells mate.} 1-0

