1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 f5 $5 {This is a tricky move.}
6. Nh3 $5 {A tricky move that carries some risk. White leaves the diagonal
from f1 to b5 unblocked so that he can meet a subsequent ...Nc6 with a pin.} (
6. d3 $1 {is simpler. White reasons that Black, having played ...f5, cannot
undermine the strong pawn at e5.}) 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 Bb4 8. Nf4 $5 {The presence
of this Knight on f4 creates unusual tactical possibilities. Here, White
threatens both Ncxd5 and -- even more dangerously for Black -- Qh5+.} 8... O-O
$1 {Unpinning by castling is an excellent response. Now White's pawn on e5 is
in danger.} 9. Ncxd5 Bc5 $2 (9... Nxe5 $1 10. Qb3 Bd6 {and now White has,
surprisingly, no good follow-up, since the attractive-looking} 11. Nxc7+ Nf7
12. Nxa8 {fails to} 12... Bxf4 {when Black is winning material.}) 10. Bc4 $2 {
Setting up a discovered check looks good, but actually Black could have taken
advantage of this.} (10. Bxc6 Bf2+ 11. Ke2 bxc6 12. Ne3 $13 {
The position is obscure, e.g.} 12... g5 $5 13. Nd3 Qd4 14. Rf1 Bh4 15. g3 g4
16. Nxg4 Bg5 17. Ne3 $13) 10... Nxe5 (10... Bf2+ 11. Kf1 Nxe5 $17) 11. Ne7+ Kh8
12. Nfg6+ Nxg6 13. Nxg6+ hxg6 14. Qh3+ {Black resigns} 1-0

