1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 $5 {This unusual move,
championed by Spielmann and Hromadka, takes the Vienna out of its normal
channels and creates very interesting problems for Black. In some lines White
gets a position that looks like an extremely favorable version of the Latvian
Gambit with colors reversed.} 5... Nxc3 $6 {
It is now generally conceded that this is not Black's best move.} (5... Nc6 {
is better.}) 6. bxc3 {
White captures this way with a view to reinforcing his e-pawn with d4.} 6...
Nc6 7. d4 Be7 8. Bd3 {So far there is no great mystery in White's play. All of
his pieces come to good squares. At this point, Black absolutely must
undermine the strong point at e5 or he will stand much worse.} 8... Be6 $6 {
This natural developing move is a step in the wrong direction.} (8... O-O 9.
Ne2 f6 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Bf4 (11. Qg3 $4 {would be a hideous mistake because of
} 11... Bh4 $19) 11... Ne7 12. O-O $16) 9. Rb1 {A free move: Black must stop
and defend b7, and White's Rook is surely more usefully placed on b1 than on
a1.} 9... Na5 10. Ne2 $1 {The Knight turns out to be very useful on this
non-standard square, since f4 is a very strong post for it.} 10... Rb8 11. O-O
{Black's position is already extremely uncomfortable.} 11... c5 {
This isn't even a real threat, since White could meet ...c4 with Bf5.} (11...
O-O 12. Nf4 {White now threatens Nxe6 followed by Qh3 when Black is very hard
put to defend h7 and e6.} 12... g6 13. Nh5 $3 (13. Qg3 {
is less spectacular but is also strong.} 13... Kh8 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bh6 Rxf1+
16. Rxf1 Qg8 17. Bg5 Bxg5 18. Qxg5 Re8 19. Rf6 Nc6 (19... Re7 20. Rxg6 hxg6 21.
Qxe7 $18) 20. Bxg6 hxg6 21. Rxg6 $18) 13... gxh5 14. Qxh5 (14. Bxh7+ {
also works, but it requires a little more finesse:} 14... Kxh7 15. Qxh5+ Kg8
16. Rf3 Bh4 {and now White has to find} 17. g3 $1 Be7 18. g4 $1 Bh4 19. Rh3)
14... f5 (14... h6 {loses in various ways, the most spectacular being} 15. Rf6
$3 (15. Bxh6 {is also crushing.}) 15... Bxf6 16. Qxh6 Re8 17. exf6 {
and Black must give up his Queen just to defer mate on g7 for a few more moves.
})) 12. Ng3 {
This move works well in the game, but it is not the only way for White to play.
} (12. Qg3 {is also very strong, with the idea of provoking ...g6 and then
causing Black trouble with Nf4xe6 when both e6 and g6 become weak.} 12... g6
13. Nf4 O-O 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bh6 $1 {This move connects Rooks without any
loss of time and sets up a perpetual niggling threat of Rf8+.} 15... Rxf1+ 16.
Rxf1 Qe8 17. Qg4 $1 $18 {and Black's Queen cannot keep an eye on both e6 and
g6. Notice that ...Bf8 is out because White can take on f8 with the Rook
thanks to the Bishop on h6.}) 12... c4 {Pushing the Bishop.} (12... O-O {
is just too dangerous for Black when White's pieces overrun the kingside, e.g.}
13. Nf5 c4 (13... Bxf5 14. Qxf5 g6 15. Qg4 c4 16. Bf5 Kh8 17. Bh6 Rg8 18. Bd7
f5 19. exf6 Bxf6 $1 {and now White proves that a Rook on b1 really is more
valuable than one on a1 by playing} 20. Rb5 $1 $18) 14. Qg3 g6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7
16. Bg5 Qa3 17. Be2 Nc6 18. Bf6 h6 19. Qh4 Kh7 20. Rf4 $1 {Not 20.Rf3, since
Black's Bishop controls the h3 square. But now the threat of a Queen sacrifice
on h6 is overwhelming. Fritz is already suggesting} 20... g5 21. Bxg5 Rh8 22.
Qxh6+ Kg8 23. Qxh8+ $1 Kxh8 24. Bf6+ Kh7 25. Rh4+ Kg6 26. Bh5+ Kf5 27. Rf1#)
13. Bf5 Qd7 (13... O-O 14. Qg4 Bxf5 15. Nxf5 g6 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Rb5 $18) 14.
Nh5 $5 {This turns out to be a very strong square for the Knight.} (14. Bxe6 $1
Qxe6 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. Rb5 Nc6 17. Ba3 $1 g6 18. Nd6+ Bxd6 19. Bxd6 Rd8 20. Rxd5
$18) 14... Bf8 (14... O-O 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Nf6+ $3 gxf6 (16... Bxf6 17. Qh5+
Kg8 18. exf6 gxf6 19. Rxf6 $18) 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Rxf6 $3 $18) 15. Qg4 Bxf5 16.
Rxf5 Nc6 17. Bh6 $1 {White exploits the bad position of Black's King and Queen,
which are vulnerable to a Knight fork at f6.} 17... Ne7 18. Nxg7+ Kd8 (18...
Bxg7 19. Qxg7 Nxf5 20. Qxh8+ Ke7 21. Bg5+ $1 f6 (21... Ke6 22. Qf6#) 22. Qxf6+
Ke8 23. Qh8+ {etc.}) 19. e6 $1 fxe6 20. Rxf8+ Rxf8 21. Nxe6+ {when the Bishop
picks up the Rook on f8, Black is just a Bishop down for nothing.} 1-0

