1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. bxc3 {This recapture
commits White to castling kingside. But it does have its benefits in the form
of reinforcing the center.} 6... Be6 7. d4 c5 {
Very reasonable: Black lashes out in the center immediately.} 8. Rb1 (8. Bb5+
Nc6 9. Ne2 {might be considered at once.}) 8... Qc7 9. Bb5+ {White wants to be
able to defend c3 with Ne2, but he does not want to bury his Bishop. This
check solves the dilemma of how to achieve both goals.} 9... Nc6 10. Ne2 O-O-O
$6 {Castling queenside here is bold; it is also arguably unwise. The open
b-file won't suffice to give White a decisive attack by itself, but it can
certainly aid in keeping up pressure on that wing.} 11. O-O {In this position,
White's Knight at e2 turns out to be surprisingly well posted, not only for
defense of dark squares such as d4 and c3 but also for active operations at f4.
} 11... Be7 12. Be3 {
Before moving the Knight to f4, White ensures that d4 is adequately supported.}
12... h5 13. Nf4 $1 Bg5 14. Nxe6 Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3 fxe6 {
Now Black's pawn at e6 could become a target.} 16. Bxc6 $6 {This move is
understandable, but it is not the most straightforward continuation.} (16. Qh3
$1 {looks like an even more direct way to take advantage of the weakness of e6.
}) 16... Qxc6 17. Rf7 {The point of White's capture on c6 was to get this Rook
to f7, However, if Black plays very accurately, White should not be able to
make anything of it.} 17... Rd7 {Of course Black defends g7.} 18. Rbf1 Rhd8 (
18... Rxf7 19. Rxf7 cxd4 20. cxd4 Qxc2 21. h3 Qxa2 22. Rxg7 Qb2 {
and White will need to find a perpetual before Black gets the a-pawn rolling.})
19. Qg5 ({It looks unnatural to retreat, but White would do better with} 19.
R7f2 $14 {The doubled Rooks still control the only open file on the board, and
the Rook at f2 defends the c-pawn, making it harder for Black to get something
for nothing on the queenside. White has the Qh3 idea to put pressure on h5 and
e6, a particularly important resource should Black go pawn hunting with
something like ...Qa4.}) 19... cxd4 20. cxd4 Rxf7 21. Rxf7 Qxc2 {This capture
looks and feels very natural. But now Black gets into serious trouble because
the c-file is fully open.} 22. Rf1 $1 {Transferring the Rook back to c1.
Black's King cannot dodge off of the c-file because the Rook on d8 hangs.}
22... Qh7 23. Qe7 $1 {Now the threat is Rc1+ with mate coming. In addition,
Black's e-pawn is hanging. There is no good way to meet both threats.} 23...
Qh6 24. h3 $6 {Here, White becomes unaccountably squeamish.} (24. Rb1 $1 {
would be immediately crushing. At first it looks like Black can meet the
threat, but actually he is helpless here.} 24... Rd7 (24... b6 25. Qxa7 $18)
25. Qf8+ Rd8 26. Qc5+ Kb8 {All other moves allow almost immediate mate.} 27.
Qe7 $18) 24... h4 25. Kh2 Qe3 26. Qxe6+ Rd7 27. Rf3 (27. Qf5 $1 {
would end the game more quickly:} 27... Qxd4 28. Rc1+ Kd8 29. Qf8#) 27... Qe1 (
27... Qg5 {was the only way to continue to put up resistance, though after} 28.
Qg8+ Rd8 29. Qf7 Rd7 30. e6 $1 {White must win.}) 28. Qf5 Kc7 29. Qc2+ Kd8 30.
Qc5 1-0

