1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 f5 6. d3 $1 {Very nice.
t the Oxford Variation, one of Black's best plans is a well-timed ...f6. Here,
he will not have that option.} (6. Nh3 $5 {is riskier.}) 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 d4 {
We now have a curious sort of Oxford Variation with the moves Qf3 and ...f5
thrown in.} 8. Qf2 dxc3 9. d4 Be6 (9... c5 $1 {
is a better idea. White should probably turn it into a pawn sacrifice:} 10.
dxc5 Nc6 11. Bb5 Qd5 12. Be3 $1 Qxe5 13. Nf3 $1 Qc7 (13... Qd5 14. O-O $1 $16)
14. O-O {Now White threatens Rae1 and Bg5, so Black has to shield the file and
get castled.} 14... Be7 15. Nd4 O-O 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bc4+ Kh8 18. Rae1 $44 {
White has enough compensation for the pawn.}) 10. Nh3 {
Heading for f4 -- a very common theme in this variation.} 10... Be7 11. Nf4 Qd7
12. Nxe6 {This is not bad, but White had a promising alternative here.} (12.
Bb5 $5 c6 (12... Qxb5 13. Nxe6 $18) 13. Nxe6 Qxe6 14. Ba4 $14 {
The Bishop on b3 will be very annoying to Black.}) 12... Qxe6 13. Bd3 g6 14.
Qe2 $6 {This shift of the Queen is needlessly provocative.} (14. Rb1 Qd5 15.
O-O $11) 14... Qd5 15. O-O $5 {
Spielmann insists on mixing things up and sacrificing his entire center.} (15.
Be3 $11 {is safe and equal.}) 15... Qxd4+ 16. Be3 Qd5 (16... Qxe5 {
looks too dangerous:} 17. Rab1 b6 18. Rbe1 Qf6 19. Bf4 $1 Nc6 20. Bb5 $1 O-O-O
21. Qf3 $1 Nb8 (21... Kb7 22. Be5 Qe6 23. Bxh8 Qd6 24. Rxe7 Qc5+ 25. Re3 Rxh8
26. Bxc6+ $18) 22. Qa8 $1 ({Or just} 22. Be5 $16) 22... Bd6 23. Rd1 {
and Black will lose a lot of material trying to prevent Bc6 and Qb7#}) 17. Rad1
Qa5 18. Bxf5 $1 {Ouch! Now Black is lost.} 18... Rf8 (18... gxf5 19. Qh5+ Kf8
20. Rxf5+ Kg7 21. Qf7#) 19. Qg4 (19. Bc8 $1 $18) 19... gxf5 20. Qh5+ Rf7 21. e6
$1 1-0

