1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Bc5 $6 {
This active-looking move creates a weakness at g7.} 7. Qg3 $1 g6 (7... O-O $2
8. Bh6 {wins the exchange immediately.}) (7... Bf5 $5 8. Bd3 (8. Qxg7 Qh4+ 9.
Qg3 Qe4+ 10. Be2 Qxc2 11. e6 Bxe6 12. Qxc7 Nd7 13. Nf3 O-O 14. Qf4 $13) 8...
Bg6 (8... Bxd3 $2 9. cxd3 {leaves Black with the same dilemma as before about
g7, and now White also has the idea of d4 available.}) 9. Bg5 Qd7 10. Ne2 h6
11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 $14) 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. h4 $1 {
Black's d-pawn is less important than the initiative on the kingside.} 11...
Nc6 12. Nf3 {Naturally White pauses to defend his center pawn.} 12... Be6 13.
h5 $1 {Oh dear! This is looking dreadful already.} 13... Rad8 14. Bd3 {
White now threatens a triple capture on g6, since if Black interposes with his
Queen, the Bishop on e6 will fall.} 14... Kg7 15. hxg6 fxg6 (15... hxg6 {
is stronger, but White wins simply by piling up on the h-file, e.g.} 16. Rh2
Rh8 17. Rdh1 Rxh2 18. Qxh2 $1 {
and Black cannot prevent a disastrous invasion down the h-file.}) 16. Rxh7+ $1
{A nice tactical wrap-up, making use of an edge trap and the availability of
the other Rook.} 16... Kxh7 17. Qxg6+ {Black resigns} 1-0

