1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Qf3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 c6 $6 {
This slack move gives White a free hand.} 7. Bf4 {
White protects e5 before Black has even attacked it and prepares 0-0-0.} 7...
Be6 (7... h5 $5 {is a funny move, more of a trap than anything else, directed
against White's plan of castling queenside. However, White can meet the threat
of ...Bg4 easily enough with} 8. Qe3 Be7 9. Nf3 h4 10. h3 Na6 11. Bd3 Nc5 12.
O-O {when White's greater space and lead in development give him a small but
pleasant plus.}) 8. O-O-O Be7 9. Nh3 $4 {This move is tactically careless.} (9.
Qg3 $1 O-O $4 10. Bh6 $18) 9... h6 $2 {Black misses his chance.} (9... g5 $1
10. Be3 g4 $19) 10. Qg3 g5 11. Be3 Na6 12. Nf2 Qa5 13. a3 (13. Kb1 $4 {
would fail here because the Bishop on e3 is vulnerable to} 13... d4 $1 $17)
13... O-O-O 14. Nd3 Nc7 15. Qf2 Nb5 16. Bc5 Bxc5 17. Nxc5 Nc7 (17... Nxc3 $1
18. bxc3 Qxa3+ 19. Kb1 d4 $1 20. cxd4 Ba2+ 21. Ka1 Bd5+ 22. Kb1 Ba2+ $11) 18.
h4 g4 19. Be2 h5 20. Rhf1 b6 $4 {Suddenly the Queen is short on squares.} 21.
Nb3 Qa4 22. Rd4 {Black resigns} 1-0

